these-- what are referred to as the War Posts that
are the clusters of driftwood and these towers

02:20:03.395 --> 02:20:07.031
that are set up along the reef and on top of the
various reefs that are shallow or breach the

02:20:07.031 --> 02:20:15.149
actual surface that have cannons attached, that
have flares set up and beacons that can be lit to

02:20:15.149 --> 02:20:20.588
alert Darktow. You get a better look this time of
the system they have to defend this island from

02:20:20.588 --> 02:20:29.019
the Clovis Concord and anybody else that would
look to make their way via ship to this island.

02:20:29.019 --> 02:20:34.857
You can see them at the ready, keeping a very
close eye on your exit as you slowly walk of shame

02:20:34.857 --> 02:20:43.929
yourselves out of the purview of the Plank King
and to a very carefully earned freedom.

02:20:43.929 --> 02:20:49.422
TRAVIS: If I may, who is really good at finding
shit? You two, and anyone--

02:20:49.422 --> 02:20:50.544
MARISHA: Like investigation style?

02:20:50.544 --> 02:20:55.633
TRAVIS: Yeah. How about you three, into Avantika's
quarters and turn it upside down.

02:20:55.633 --> 02:20:59.429
MARISHA: Ooh, you are turning me on right now.

02:20:59.429 --> 02:21:00.685
TRAVIS: Not my intention, but go ahead.

02:21:00.685 --> 02:21:01.306
MARISHA: Yes!

02:21:01.306 --> 02:21:01.981
TRAVIS: Okay.

02:21:01.981 --> 02:21:08.330
TRAVIS: Just in case she booby trapped this ship,
search the hull, search her quarters, search everything.

02:21:08.330 --> 02:21:10.595
MARISHA: Yeah, check for traps first, okay?

02:21:10.595 --> 02:21:12.193
LIAM: I'll be doing that at disadvantage.

02:21:12.193 --> 02:21:13.468
TALIESIN: I'm going to try and calm the crew a
little bit.

02:21:13.468 --> 02:21:14.108
MATT: Okay.

02:21:14.108 --> 02:21:20.588
TALIESIN: I'll point out that we're-- this is all
good. We got away from the pirates, everything's all right.

02:21:20.588 --> 02:21:26.377
MATT: Make a general persuasion check for me. Just
a persuasion check.

02:21:27.876 --> 02:21:29.172
TALIESIN: That's 15.

02:21:29.172 --> 02:21:35.625
MATT: Okay, you do. A number of the crew that you
hired, some of them look like they're a little

02:21:35.649 --> 02:21:41.435
scarred from the experience, but you managed to
calm them down. They seem very thankful that

02:21:41.595 --> 02:21:45.224
you've pulled them-- you brought them into this
mess, but you pulled them out of it and there's

02:21:45.224 --> 02:21:52.846
something to that. Some of them begin to get back
to work, begin to repair some of the aspects of

02:21:52.846 --> 02:21:58.388
the ship. Man.

02:21:58.388 --> 02:22:01.274
TRAVIS: Is Jester able to mend some of those
damaged--?

02:22:01.274 --> 02:22:05.403
LAURA: That's what I was going to try to do, yeah.
Anything that's small enough, I'm going to try to

02:22:05.403 --> 02:22:07.068
mend. Small holes.

02:22:07.068 --> 02:22:08.080
LIAM: 20 percent of the damage?

02:22:08.080 --> 02:22:08.916
LAURA: Yeah.

02:22:08.916 --> 02:22:13.646
MATT: There are a few places, but for the most
part-- and it's only the one mast. You still have

02:22:13.646 --> 02:22:18.645
enough sails because it's a three-mast ship. You
can still coast the winds, but it's not going to

02:22:18.645 --> 02:22:24.022
be optimal speed. You'll have to get back to some
sort of a port to get the rest of the sails

02:22:24.022 --> 02:22:30.080
repaired because you don't have replacement sails.
The downside of the Fireball. The Fireball and

02:22:30.080 --> 02:22:34.495
the-- actually. It was a 20-foot tall Wall of
Fire.

02:22:34.495 --> 02:22:36.411
LIAM: Yes, but the upside was so--

02:22:36.411 --> 02:22:37.652
MATT: It was.

02:22:37.652 --> 02:22:39.809
SAM: Then you singed the other sails, too.

02:22:39.809 --> 02:22:41.328
MATT: Yeah, there's a lot of sail-- you have--

02:22:41.328 --> 02:22:46.110
LIAM: Yeah, 20 feet tall. For six to 12 seconds.
That didn't last more than two rounds.

02:22:46.110 --> 02:22:47.988
MATT: I know, but that's a very intense--

02:22:47.988 --> 02:22:49.060
LIAM: Absolutely.

02:22:49.060 --> 02:22:55.753
MATT: I would say comparatively, you're limping on
one full mast of functionality, and the rest of

02:22:55.753 --> 02:22:57.488
the sails are partially damaged.

02:22:57.488 --> 02:22:59.703
LIAM: (gasps) (pigeon coos) Paint on the mast.

02:22:59.703 --> 02:23:04.347
LAURA: (pigeon coo) I was thinking about it, but
it's a lot of the use of the paint because--

02:23:04.347 --> 02:23:06.653
SAM: (pigeon coo) How about a few sails?

02:23:06.653 --> 02:23:13.818
TALIESIN: We don't have to pigeon this. I mean, we
know what you can do, so maybe paint the fix for it.

02:23:13.818 --> 02:23:15.283
MATT: Just so you know--

02:23:15.283 --> 02:23:17.598
LAURA: That's what I want. I don't want to paint
the whole thing.

02:23:17.598 --> 02:23:24.337
MATT: Just so you know, this ship travels on an
average pace of around 48 miles a day. Right now

02:23:24.337 --> 02:23:28.961
with the damage the sails have sustained, you're
close to 20. You're less than half speed on the

02:23:28.961 --> 02:23:36.495
ship with the damage it's sustained at the sails.
It's going to take you a while to get anywhere.

02:23:36.495 --> 02:23:37.988
But you have it.

02:23:37.988 --> 02:23:40.906
LAURA: How big are the holes? Are they giant?

02:23:40.906 --> 02:23:42.005
MATT: They're beyond Mending.

02:23:42.005 --> 02:23:42.698
LAURA: Okay.

02:23:42.698 --> 02:23:44.467
MATT: Mending can do little tears and things.

02:23:44.467 --> 02:23:47.668
LAURA: No, I'm not talking Mending, I'm talking
how big are the holes?

02:23:47.668 --> 02:23:53.038
MATT: For the ones that are damaged, the sails are
mostly destroyed. They caught fire and burned.

02:23:53.038 --> 02:24:01.535
LIAM: I have a question. If I finally go to bed
for like 14 hours-- Minor Alchemy for a

02:24:01.535 --> 02:24:07.382
transmutation wizard. I am able to perform an
alchemical procedure on one object composed

02:24:07.382 --> 02:24:13.672
entirely of wood, stone, iron, copper, silver, and
transform it into another material. If there was

02:24:13.672 --> 02:24:18.658
damage to the mast, would I be able to shove other
things in there and turn it to wood? That seems

02:24:18.658 --> 02:24:21.161
like too much.

02:24:21.161 --> 02:24:23.245
MATT: Doesn't quite work that way, and it's
temporary. It's more--

02:24:23.245 --> 02:24:27.139
LIAM: It's a spell that I could've done, but I
didn't take that spell. I chose Counterspell.

02:24:27.139 --> 02:24:30.464
MATT: To be fair, I think that worked in your
favor. If tonight has proved anything, if the end

02:24:30.464 --> 02:24:33.606
of the last campaign has proved anything,
Counterspell's always a good choice.

02:24:33.606 --> 02:24:37.025
TALIESIN: We're going to spend a day moving
slowly, but I think we're going to slowly figure

02:24:37.025 --> 02:24:43.242
out how, between all of us, we can repair this,
and I'm sure we can figure out where to get some cloth.

02:24:43.242 --> 02:24:45.794
MARISHA: This just turned into a resource
management game.

02:24:45.794 --> 02:24:47.279
TALIESIN: Yeah, it's a lot different kind of
game.

02:24:47.279 --> 02:24:52.525
MATT: You guys have now pushed into the rest of
the seafaring mist. It takes you a while to move

02:24:52.525 --> 02:24:56.595
beyond the Dragshallow Reef, the better part of
the day before you escape the channel at the pace

02:24:56.595 --> 02:25:02.684
you're moving. The clouds are pretty heavy now.
The open sky that you enjoyed on your way to

02:25:02.684 --> 02:25:09.401
Darktow has now become-- not a storm front by any
means, but definitely cloudier skies. As you're

02:25:09.401 --> 02:25:16.943
heading outside, you can see Yasha smelling the
air and be like, "This might be getting close to

02:25:16.943 --> 02:25:19.629
"storm weather."

02:25:19.629 --> 02:25:20.982
TRAVIS: Is that a good thing?

02:25:20.982 --> 02:25:22.311
MATT: She smiles.

02:25:22.311 --> 02:25:25.457
TRAVIS: It's a good thing.

02:25:25.457 --> 02:25:30.546
MATT: Continuing past into that space, repairs are
being done best you can, with the ship still

02:25:30.546 --> 02:25:35.076
limping along. You make your way out of the
Dragshallow Reef, out into open waters, and the

02:25:35.076 --> 02:25:36.746
ocean is yours.

02:25:36.746 --> 02:25:38.448
TRAVIS: Can I find Orly?

02:25:38.448 --> 02:25:39.162
MATT: Yeah.

02:25:39.162 --> 02:25:41.720
TRAVIS: I'll bring out the map.

02:25:41.720 --> 02:25:44.400
MATT: Bring out the map.

02:25:44.400 --> 02:25:45.864
TRAVIS: I don't have it near me.

02:25:45.864 --> 02:25:47.095
LAURA: Should we get close to a port or
something?

02:25:47.095 --> 02:25:48.168
TALIESIN: Or an island where we--

02:25:48.168 --> 02:25:50.242
TRAVIS: Do we know where the map is, please?

02:25:50.242 --> 02:25:51.964
SAM: (singing) Bring out the map!

02:25:51.964 --> 02:25:57.304
MATT: It's usually right there. It got moved for
Honey Heist, that's why. Oh, is it down there? Oh,

02:25:57.304 --> 02:25:59.912
there it is! It got hidden! It got moved from me!

02:25:59.912 --> 02:26:00.599
TRAVIS: Damn it, Bobby!

02:26:00.599 --> 02:26:02.624
MATT: Damn it, Bobby. There you go.

02:26:02.624 --> 02:26:05.421
LIAM: I sell falchions and--

02:26:05.421 --> 02:26:09.953
MARISHA: I'm having an adrenaline crash now.

02:26:09.953 --> 02:26:11.817
LIAM: Yeah, we survived and--

02:26:11.817 --> 02:26:14.830
MARISHA: Are those little zoomy magnifying
glasses?

02:26:14.830 --> 02:26:17.130
LIAM: They're magnifying, Matt? Where'd you get
those?

02:26:17.130 --> 02:26:21.687
MARISHA: The crew got them. That was Max. Thanks,
producer Max!

02:26:21.687 --> 02:26:25.359
TRAVIS: Do we know if we are making our way--?

02:26:25.359 --> 02:26:29.125
MATT: You guys have just managed to make your way
out of here.

02:26:29.125 --> 02:26:31.188
SAM: Oh, going the wrong way.

02:26:31.188 --> 02:26:34.698
LIAM: So we're going right into her vagina.

02:26:34.698 --> 02:26:38.232
MATT: Well, that is the Wildmother. She is nature,
I guess.

02:26:38.232 --> 02:26:44.852
TRAVIS: I'll tell Orly: Orly, if you could help us
plot a course, as damaged as we are, heading north

02:26:44.852 --> 02:26:47.403
to this point.

02:26:47.403 --> 02:26:50.082
LAURA: Shouldn't we get to a port or something
before we--?

02:26:50.082 --> 02:26:51.181
SAM: Yeah, we need to repair first.

02:26:51.181 --> 02:26:52.205
LIAM: There ain't no fucking port around here,
motherfucker.

02:26:52.205 --> 02:26:58.225
SAM: Well, maybe there's something over here! He
knows about something. Let's ask! Orly? M-m-maybe?

02:26:58.225 --> 02:27:00.258
TRAVIS: Wow.

02:27:00.258 --> 02:27:08.191
LIAM: Max Headroom, coming at you from the
mid-80s! W-w-what?

02:27:08.191 --> 02:27:11.175
MATT: It's a good thing I grew up a stutterer.

02:27:11.175 --> 02:27:16.861
LIAM: Yeah. Matt is just barely old enough to know
what that is.

02:27:16.861 --> 02:27:18.392
MATT: Oh, I know Max Headroom.

02:27:18.392 --> 02:27:21.596
LIAM: I said you know what it is! Just barely.

02:27:21.596 --> 02:27:25.560
MATT: It's funny, I didn't realize who played him
until years later and I was like, really, him?

02:27:25.560 --> 02:27:27.019
TRAVIS: Wait, who played him?

02:27:27.019 --> 02:27:28.623
MATT: Oh, what's the actor?

02:27:28.623 --> 02:27:32.493
LIAM: He was in The Stand as the Trashcan Man.

02:27:32.493 --> 02:27:38.622
MATT: He was, and he played the part of Jobe in
Lawnmower Man 2. Anyway!

02:27:38.622 --> 02:27:48.482
TRAVIS: Because this is on a trade run, and this
whole isle is part of that, could we make port for

02:27:48.482 --> 02:27:50.884
more extensive repairs there?

02:27:50.884 --> 02:27:55.146
MATT: It's a resource stop. It might have some
repairs, in your experience. It's not a major port

02:27:55.146 --> 02:27:58.852
by any means, it's more of a small--

02:27:58.852 --> 02:27:59.826
TRAVIS: Resupply?

02:27:59.826 --> 02:28:00.663
MATT: Yeah, it's a resupply.

02:28:00.663 --> 02:28:02.083
LAURA: Might have canvas, at least.

02:28:02.083 --> 02:28:03.657
TALIESIN: We can use Divination.

02:28:03.657 --> 02:28:04.763
TRAVIS: That's the closest thing.

02:28:04.763 --> 02:28:06.102
MATT: From your experience--

02:28:06.102 --> 02:28:08.706
TRAVIS: Divination? What do you mean?

02:28:08.706 --> 02:28:14.429
TALIESIN: If it's been 24 hours-- once I have a
long rest, I can take my morning meditation and

02:28:14.429 --> 02:28:20.291
ask the Wildmother if there's a place of calm for
our boat.

02:28:20.291 --> 02:28:21.752
LAURA: You can do that?

02:28:21.752 --> 02:28:22.714
TALIESIN: I can do a lot of stuff, man.

02:28:22.714 --> 02:28:24.932
TRAVIS: I would love to have you do that.

02:28:24.932 --> 02:28:26.638
LIAM: Are you doing that?

02:28:26.638 --> 02:28:30.033
TALIESIN: I was going to do that. Yeah.

02:28:30.033 --> 02:28:38.416
MATT: To answer your question, Orly goes, "Yeah.
There's a way to get that working for you. We'll

02:28:38.416 --> 02:28:51.646
"all take course and head for that m-m-mighty
dangerous part of the sea." He marks it and they

02:28:51.646 --> 02:28:55.574
set it. You guys have been making your way around
the Dragshallow northward towards that area.

02:28:55.574 --> 02:28:57.708
SAM: Is that past where we're going?

02:28:57.859 --> 02:28:59.861
TRAVIS: It is, but we don't have any other--

02:28:59.861 --> 02:29:03.337
TALIESIN: Yeah, in the early morning I'm going to
go to the crow's nest and have a ten-minute

02:29:03.337 --> 02:29:10.392
meditation and ask the Wildmother which direction
we should be heading to find some safe harbor to

02:29:10.392 --> 02:29:13.632
heal ourselves and heal our boat.

02:29:13.632 --> 02:29:15.810
MATT: Okay. Is this an ability, or--

02:29:15.810 --> 02:29:18.850
TALIESIN: Yes, it is a 4th-level spell, it's
Divination.

02:29:18.850 --> 02:29:20.433
MATT: Oh, there we go.

02:29:20.433 --> 02:29:27.981
TALIESIN: I'm using it. It takes ten minutes, and
you can be as obtuse as you like. You can be a

02:29:27.981 --> 02:29:30.984
bird that flies in a direction, an insect, or
whatever.

02:29:30.984 --> 02:29:34.014
TRAVIS: Thank you for the Shawshank obtuse
reference.

02:29:34.014 --> 02:29:44.249
MATT: Okay, yeah. The Wildmother responds--
Actually, let me see what will be the best answer

02:29:44.249 --> 02:29:54.998
to this one, give me just a second. (stage
whisper) Talk amongst yourselves.

02:29:54.998 --> 02:30:01.570
TALIESIN: I was seeing if there was anything else
I can do-- I'm setting day two spells so we'll

02:30:01.570 --> 02:30:02.938
have food and water.

02:30:02.938 --> 02:30:09.108
LIAM: If we're talking about, like business shit,
Caleb is going to Beau and saying: I'm sorry, I

02:30:09.108 --> 02:30:14.850
know that this has been less than ten days, but I
need my cat, so I am taking my owl, I apologize.

02:30:14.850 --> 02:30:28.709
On a side note, so impressed. I walk off with my
little tiny one-ounce owl.

02:30:28.709 --> 02:30:29.755
MARISHA: Bye, Frumpkin.

02:30:29.755 --> 02:30:35.173
LIAM: I will take the time to turn Frumpkin- I
have two uses left with incense- back into a

02:30:35.173 --> 02:30:42.847
Bengal cat. So he can live his best life as a
Bengal cat.

02:30:42.847 --> 02:30:45.417
SAM: (imitating Liam's accent) Bengal cat.

02:30:45.417 --> 02:30:48.055
LIAM: Diplomatic cat-munity.

02:30:58.592 --> 02:31:04.544
MATT: You get that situated. Anybody else doing
anything?

02:31:04.544 --> 02:31:06.389
LAURA: I'm going to--

02:31:06.389 --> 02:31:16.232
MATT: Your answer, by the way, is: "Bisaft Isle
brings you safest harbor in what you seek."

02:31:16.232 --> 02:31:19.962
TALIESIN and SAM: Bisaft.

02:31:19.962 --> 02:31:28.614
MATT: There's a warm, gentle embrace that comes
with the words, an understanding, and a familiar

02:31:28.614 --> 02:31:37.927
matronly guidance that brings you calm on the
ocean seas that have long brought you anxiety. For

02:31:37.927 --> 02:31:41.823
the first time in probably a good number of weeks,
you get to walk out on that deck, take a deep

02:31:41.823 --> 02:31:46.598
breath of ocean air, and feel really confident.

02:31:46.598 --> 02:31:56.709
TALIESIN: Sea smells different today. Might just
be the charred boat and-- Oh, no. Bisaft.

02:31:56.709 --> 02:31:58.876
TRAVIS: You look rejuvenated. Did you say Bisaft?

02:31:58.876 --> 02:32:04.122
TALIESIN: Bisaft. We're to head towards Bisaft.

02:32:04.122 --> 02:32:05.983
TRAVIS: You're sure?

02:32:05.983 --> 02:32:08.426
TALIESIN: Sure as anything.

02:32:08.426 --> 02:32:10.969
TRAVIS: All right then. You can let Orly know.

02:32:10.969 --> 02:32:12.960
TALIESIN: Orly!

02:32:12.960 --> 02:32:15.819
MATT: "Mm-hmm?"

02:32:15.819 --> 02:32:17.439
TALIESIN: Know the Isle of Bisaft?

02:32:17.439 --> 02:32:20.182
MATT: "Oh, I'm quite familiar."

02:32:20.182 --> 02:32:24.217
TALIESIN: That seem to be the direction we're
heading right now?

02:32:24.217 --> 02:32:31.225
MATT: "About as close as any direction gets,
really." Other eye, even.

02:32:31.225 --> 02:32:35.276
TALIESIN: I think that might be the place we ought
to go.

02:32:35.776 --> 02:32:46.988
MATT: Making it jump around a bit, guys. "Mm. Very
well. M-m-make sure to point this ship in that direction."

02:32:46.988 --> 02:32:48.124
TALIESIN: Thank you.

02:32:48.124 --> 02:32:50.214
MATT: "And you."

02:32:51.091 --> 02:32:56.800
SAM: On the first day we were on this boat, me and
Beau and others were going to go into Avantika's

02:32:56.800 --> 02:32:58.562
cabin and snoop around.

02:32:58.562 --> 02:33:04.823
LIAM: Oh right. I rolled an 18 and a 19 ten
minutes ago.

02:33:04.823 --> 02:33:08.460
MARISHA: I don't know if I rolled. I don't think I
did.

02:33:08.460 --> 02:33:12.824
SAM: I didn't roll yet either, but I was going to
crawl in through the hole in her floor if it's

02:33:12.824 --> 02:33:14.024
still there.

02:33:14.024 --> 02:33:15.056
MATT: Oh, it's still there.

02:33:15.056 --> 02:33:21.052
SAM: To avoid any traps, and then look around the
door from the inside to see if she had trapped it

02:33:21.052 --> 02:33:22.555
or anything.

02:33:22.555 --> 02:33:25.367
MATT: Okay. Make an investigation check on that.

02:33:26.528 --> 02:33:28.761
SAM: 20. 19.

02:33:28.761 --> 02:33:29.968
MATT: No, it is not trapped.

02:33:29.968 --> 02:33:31.901
SAM: I'll open it and let you guys in.

02:33:31.901 --> 02:33:41.579
LIAM: I rolled an investigation check ten minutes
ago at disadvantage and the lower is a 27. My

02:33:41.579 --> 02:33:44.185
investigation is plus eight. I'm smart--

02:33:44.185 --> 02:33:45.330
MATT: The lower was 19?

02:33:45.330 --> 02:33:47.858
LIAM: Yes. I rolled an 18 and a 19.

02:33:47.858 --> 02:33:51.544
SAM: Well, I'll show Caleb around the room that
I've already been in to see if he can find

02:33:51.544 --> 02:33:53.230
anything else.

02:33:53.230 --> 02:33:56.556
MARISHA: I'm in there too.

02:33:56.556 --> 02:34:05.630
MATT: Glancing around, you find-- There's her
dresser with a number of outfits, coats, shirts,

02:34:05.630 --> 02:34:12.481
things that belong to the captain that you guys
get to distribute as you see fit.

02:34:12.481 --> 02:34:14.717
LAURA: (cartoon voice) Hey, look at me! I'm
Avantika!

02:34:14.717 --> 02:34:16.762
LIAM: Are there any more gigantic hats?

02:34:16.762 --> 02:34:18.779
MARISHA: I was going to say teddies, but...

02:34:18.779 --> 02:34:20.089
MATT: There's a few hats, yeah.

02:34:20.089 --> 02:34:21.465
LIAM: Gigantic hats.

02:34:21.465 --> 02:34:22.576
MATT: Avantika-sized hats.

02:34:22.576 --> 02:34:26.842
MARISHA and TALIESIN: (singing) Hats and teddies.
Hats, hats, and teddies.

02:34:26.842 --> 02:34:33.290
(laughter)

02:34:33.290 --> 02:34:38.488
SAM: Does she have a fragrance or anything? Like a
perfume?

02:34:38.488 --> 02:34:40.446
MARISHA: Chanel No. 5.

02:34:40.446 --> 02:34:45.641
MATT: I will say you do find some scented oils,
but that's the extent.

02:34:45.641 --> 02:34:46.717
SAM: I'll take those.

02:34:46.717 --> 02:34:48.502
MATT: She's not a perfume keeper.

02:34:48.502 --> 02:34:50.741
TALIESIN: How about that statue above the door?

02:34:50.741 --> 02:34:53.073
LAURA: Yeah, her little altar.

02:34:53.073 --> 02:34:56.111
MATT: The altar is still there, the altar to
Uk'otoa.

02:34:56.111 --> 02:35:01.180
MARISHA: The maps-- the stuff behind her, charting
out where she was going, anything in there?

02:35:01.180 --> 02:35:11.211
MATT: Yeah. You find a few other maps and things
that refer to a-- You see it breaking down the

02:35:11.211 --> 02:35:15.413
different trade routes, and you see other paths
breaking out; those that try and avoid the trade

02:35:15.413 --> 02:35:19.340
routes to avoid the pirates. Those different paths
they might take at different times of the year to

02:35:19.340 --> 02:35:23.855
try and head off people that are trying to avoid
the waters that they're looking in. You find maps

02:35:23.855 --> 02:35:31.789
that deal with the path to Urukayxl, and you see
the handwritten map by Jamedi that was the path

02:35:31.789 --> 02:35:38.598
you guys were lead through on Urukayxl to find the
temple. You find another map that has circled

02:35:38.598 --> 02:35:47.116
heavily the archipelago that you've already sussed
out, and you find recent notes on that same map

02:35:47.116 --> 02:35:53.528
that refer to the loose area circled where your
ship went down that time ago.

02:35:53.597 --> 02:35:59.444
TRAVIS: Will we pass over that area as we're
heading towards Bisaft?

02:35:59.444 --> 02:36:06.873
MATT: Well, you'll get near that area. If you want
to head that way, you can let Orly know to--

02:36:06.873 --> 02:36:08.309
MARISHA: It's on the way...

02:36:08.309 --> 02:36:09.762
LIAM: Are you in this room with us too, right
now?

02:36:09.762 --> 02:36:12.432
TRAVIS: No, I'm just asking.

02:36:12.432 --> 02:36:18.514
MATT: You find a lot of those materials. You get
the sense that, aside from the maps, most of the

02:36:18.514 --> 02:36:21.217
information that she had, she kept in that book.

02:36:21.217 --> 02:36:28.981
MARISHA: Any supplies list? Any inventory: canvas
on board, things to make supplies?

02:36:28.981 --> 02:36:31.676
MATT: You find a number of fine cheeses,
actually.

02:36:31.676 --> 02:36:35.903
MARISHA: Chocolate dipped strawberries,
champ-pag-nay.

02:36:35.903 --> 02:36:40.756
MATT: Not quite. All the good food was kept for
the captain and some of it's turning a little, but

02:36:40.756 --> 02:36:51.134
it's cheese. Some better treats and some sugared
candies that were kept specifically, like a

02:36:51.134 --> 02:36:54.058
private stash for the captain, you manage to
find.

02:36:54.058 --> 02:36:59.605
SAM: While we're down there, looking around, I'm
going to say: So, you know, it's just the three of

02:36:59.605 --> 02:37:01.414
us down here.

02:37:01.414 --> 02:37:03.178
LIAM: Yeah. I'm sitting on the bed right now.

02:37:03.178 --> 02:37:06.034
SAM: We have some secrets between us already.

02:37:06.034 --> 02:37:09.443
MARISHA: Yeah, it's been a while since just the
three of us have been in a room together.

02:37:09.443 --> 02:37:17.960
LIAM: Wait a second, look at me. I'm sitting on
the bed. I am the servant of a demigod. This is

02:37:17.960 --> 02:37:20.537
going to be very hard for Fjord.

02:37:20.537 --> 02:37:22.258
SAM: Yes, well...

02:37:22.258 --> 02:37:25.010
MARISHA: What? You're jumping around so much.

02:37:25.010 --> 02:37:30.644
LIAM: We can get back to what you're talking
about, but think about it for a moment; it's just

02:37:30.644 --> 02:37:39.254
the three of us, right? We have our heads in the
same game. We are the three assholes in this

02:37:39.254 --> 02:37:40.820
group, yeah?

02:37:40.820 --> 02:37:45.158
SAM: I'm asshole adjacent.

02:37:45.158 --> 02:37:47.040
MARISHA: She's quite pleasant, actually.

02:37:47.040 --> 02:37:48.314
LIAM: That is correct.

02:37:48.314 --> 02:37:51.071
MARISHA: She might be better than both of us
combined.

02:37:51.071 --> 02:37:57.830
LIAM: I'm joking because this has been such a hard
day, but Fjord is going to find this very difficult.

02:37:57.830 --> 02:38:00.680
SAM: We're going to protect him, like we always
do.

02:38:00.680 --> 02:38:05.807
MARISHA: Which part difficult? Losing his fuck
buddy? It's not that difficult.

02:38:05.807 --> 02:38:14.044
LIAM: That is minimalizing what he is dealing with
right now. He is trying to find a father, he has

02:38:14.044 --> 02:38:20.192
compromised himself with this woman for us, for
himself, for all of our safety. It is going to be

02:38:20.192 --> 02:38:21.470
difficult for him.

02:38:21.470 --> 02:38:28.369
MARISHA: Of course it's minimalizing, have you met
me? Everything I do is minimalizing.

02:38:28.369 --> 02:38:31.282
LIAM: You have your pluses and your minuses.

02:38:31.282 --> 02:38:41.591
SAM: Speaking of your pluses: the Expositors?
You're special forces, did I hear that correctly?

02:38:41.591 --> 02:38:43.582
Is that what you are called?

02:38:43.582 --> 02:38:44.493
MARISHA: Yeah.

02:38:44.493 --> 02:38:48.125
SAM: Is that true? It seemed pretty true.

02:38:48.125 --> 02:38:50.932
MARISHA: Yeah, what Caleb said.

02:38:50.932 --> 02:38:52.216
LIAM: It's mostly true.

02:38:52.216 --> 02:38:53.917
SAM: What do you mean-- How do you know?

02:38:53.917 --> 02:38:56.769
MARISHA: Yeah, how do you know?

02:38:56.769 --> 02:39:03.694
LIAM: She is too educated. She is too in-the-know
to talk the way she does, to be interested in just

02:39:03.694 --> 02:39:13.132
drinking and chasing our barbarian friend. She is
very educated. I don't know which parts are true.

02:39:13.132 --> 02:39:17.072
SAM: Well, which parts are true?

02:39:17.072 --> 02:39:18.912
MARISHA: You want to take a guess?

02:39:18.912 --> 02:39:26.167
SAM: I think you're a secret agent! I think you're
on a dangerous mission- a life or death mission-

02:39:26.167 --> 02:39:32.389
to find bad guys and take them down! To get the
collar and bring them in to the po-po, or

02:39:32.389 --> 02:39:35.931
something. I don't know how it works! I'm not a
secret agent, you are!

02:39:35.931 --> 02:39:40.444
MARISHA: It's very romanticized, but on that note:
Caleb, do you think you could recreate that cipher

02:39:40.444 --> 02:39:44.463
that you made and have one on hand?

02:39:44.526 --> 02:39:47.002
LIAM: Of course. That is easy.

02:39:47.002 --> 02:39:49.445
MARISHA: I'd like a copy, if you don't mind.

02:39:49.445 --> 02:39:53.161
LIAM: Sure, what are friends for.

02:39:53.161 --> 02:39:55.927
SAM: Do you have a license to kill?

02:39:56.978 --> 02:40:06.781
MARISHA: Got them right here, Nott. Just these--
No, that wasn't working? No? All right. Yeah, it's

02:40:06.781 --> 02:40:12.055
a little true, but not as intense as you think.

02:40:12.055 --> 02:40:14.164
SAM: Are there others like you?

02:40:14.164 --> 02:40:15.986
MARISHA: Monks?

02:40:15.986 --> 02:40:18.100
SAM: No, like--

02:40:18.100 --> 02:40:19.381
MARISHA: Expositors?

02:40:19.381 --> 02:40:20.810
SAM: Yeah, Delta Force.

02:40:20.810 --> 02:40:22.218
MARISHA: Yes.

02:40:22.218 --> 02:40:27.508
SAM: How do you know who's who? Do you have a
sign? Secret handshake?

02:40:28.979 --> 02:40:31.988
MARISHA: Kind of new to it all, to be honest.

02:40:35.010 --> 02:40:37.622
SAM: You guys are really cool.

02:40:37.622 --> 02:40:42.993
LIAM: No. I am looking forward to getting back to
the mainland, and I don't mean the Menagerie

02:40:42.993 --> 02:40:50.759
Coast. Although... We need to get Jester back to
her mother if we can, but I am not looking forward

02:40:50.759 --> 02:40:54.380
to being here anymore. I want to get back to the
Empire.

02:40:54.380 --> 02:41:01.769
MARISHA: Speaking of time that it takes to travel,
are we sure that Avantika was the only one who was

02:41:01.769 --> 02:41:05.987
interested in what Uk'otoa has to offer?

02:41:05.987 --> 02:41:12.779
LIAM: Well, there is still Vandren. I have read
every inch of her notes, I have communicated them to you.

02:41:12.779 --> 02:41:18.646
MARISHA: I guess what I'm saying is, are we still
going to be competing against others once the

02:41:18.646 --> 02:41:22.729
Plank King successfully deciphers that book?

02:41:22.729 --> 02:41:31.804
LIAM: I would imagine the Plank King would not
know what to make of it. It clearly damns her. It

02:41:31.804 --> 02:41:35.851
does not give him enough information-- He wouldn't
know what to do with it.

02:41:35.851 --> 02:41:37.698
MARISHA: It does kind of sound like a wives'
tale.

02:41:37.698 --> 02:41:44.263
LIAM: Yeah, he's not a big thinker. He is
formidable, but not a big thinker. I think we will

02:41:44.263 --> 02:41:47.140
have an easier time getting to this boat.

02:41:47.140 --> 02:41:51.100
MARISHA: Let's go talk about it with the others, I
think.

02:41:51.100 --> 02:41:55.879
SAM: Your secret is safe with me.

02:41:56.647 --> 02:41:59.247
LAURA: Above deck, can I go find Fjord?

02:41:59.247 --> 02:42:00.978
MATT: Yeah.

02:42:00.978 --> 02:42:06.861
LAURA: So... that happened. (giggles)

02:42:06.861 --> 02:42:08.862
TRAVIS: Yeah.

02:42:08.862 --> 02:42:12.567
LAURA: How do you feel about it?

02:42:12.567 --> 02:42:15.140
TRAVIS: Relieved.

02:42:15.140 --> 02:42:16.303
LAURA: Yeah?

02:42:16.303 --> 02:42:22.951
TRAVIS: Yeah. I was worried for a moment there. I
knew it was going to come to something like that,

02:42:22.951 --> 02:42:25.709
but Caleb pulling the trigger the way he did
was--

02:42:25.709 --> 02:42:28.542
LAURA: Did he cause that explosion?

02:42:28.542 --> 02:42:30.007
TRAVIS: Yeah.

02:42:30.007 --> 02:42:31.512
LAURA: Wow.

02:42:31.512 --> 02:42:32.487
TRAVIS: Right.

02:42:32.487 --> 02:42:34.197
LAURA: He did a lot of damage.

02:42:34.197 --> 02:42:38.469
TRAVIS: He did. He's very strong.

02:42:38.469 --> 02:42:45.492
LAURA: So now we're going to find the place where
your ship wrecked, yeah?

02:42:45.492 --> 02:42:48.468
TRAVIS: I think so, yeah.

02:42:48.468 --> 02:42:52.124
LAURA: You didn't get to ask them about Vandren,
though.

02:42:52.557 --> 02:43:05.409
TRAVIS: No, I didn't. It hurts to see so many
react to a name that only meant so much to me,

02:43:05.409 --> 02:43:12.325
but-- I don't even know if he's alive. We might
find him down there.

02:43:12.611 --> 02:43:21.686
LAURA: Wow. Do you think if we find him, you'll
stop talking like him?

02:43:24.467 --> 02:43:27.413
TRAVIS: We'll see.

02:43:28.908 --> 02:43:32.778
LAURA: You know, I could probably send a message
to the Plank King and ask him about Vandren, if

02:43:32.778 --> 02:43:34.630
you want me to.

02:43:34.923 --> 02:43:36.324
TRAVIS: What do you mean?

02:43:36.324 --> 02:43:41.281
LAURA: Well, I can send him a message the same way
I try to talk to my mama, and the Gentleman, and

02:43:41.281 --> 02:43:43.642
Kiri sometimes.

02:43:43.642 --> 02:43:46.512
TRAVIS: You send messages to Kiri?

02:43:46.512 --> 02:43:47.448
LAURA: Yeah.

02:43:47.448 --> 02:43:48.669
TRAVIS: What do you say?

02:43:48.669 --> 02:43:53.362
LAURA: Oh, just that she's really cute, and that I
miss her, and I wish I could see her, and I hope

02:43:53.362 --> 02:44:00.798
she's enjoying herself, and that I am sorry that
we haven't seen each other in a while, and that we

02:44:00.798 --> 02:44:03.260
are pirates, and--

02:44:03.260 --> 02:44:06.776
TRAVIS: Can she respond to these messages?

02:44:06.776 --> 02:44:15.976
LAURA: She usually responds with, "We're pirates,
and I miss you, and--"

02:44:15.976 --> 02:44:17.326
TRAVIS: (as Jester) Go fuck yourself.

02:44:17.326 --> 02:44:21.908
LAURA: No, she doesn't say that. She says, "Yes,
I'm very cute," a lot.

02:44:21.908 --> 02:44:27.770
TRAVIS: Right. I suppose, what would you put in
the letter to the Plank King?

02:44:27.770 --> 02:44:30.077
LAURA: Whatever you want me to.

02:44:30.077 --> 02:44:46.318
TRAVIS: I mean, I don't know if it's necessary. I
can't think of anything as of yet. I don't know,

02:44:46.318 --> 02:44:49.215
maybe I'll just let you know. Thank you for
offering, though.

02:44:49.215 --> 02:44:52.864
LAURA: Of course. Your teeth are coming in.

02:44:52.864 --> 02:44:56.159
TRAVIS: Yeah.

02:44:56.159 --> 02:45:00.627
LAURA: I saw it peek out of your lip just now.

02:45:00.627 --> 02:45:10.928
TRAVIS: Okay, all right. Yeah. Thank you for not
telling the others.

02:45:10.928 --> 02:45:14.780
LAURA: Of course, Fjord.

02:45:17.539 --> 02:45:20.093
TRAVIS: I've got to go check on Orly, make sure
we're going the right way.

02:45:20.093 --> 02:45:23.075
LAURA: Yeah, I'm going to go see if everything's
mended over this way.

02:45:25.032 --> 02:45:27.335
MARISHA: Mended over this way.

02:45:30.282 --> 02:45:33.330
LIAM: Put a piece of paper back together.

02:45:34.798 --> 02:45:43.483
MATT: It's going to take you about a week to get
to the location that you're seeking.

02:45:43.483 --> 02:45:45.703
MARISHA: The boat or the island?

02:45:45.703 --> 02:45:47.720
TRAVIS: The island.

02:45:47.720 --> 02:45:53.393
MATT: No, the island's going to take longer than
that-- to get to where the last time you recall

02:45:53.393 --> 02:45:54.827
your ship going down.

02:45:54.827 --> 02:45:57.037
MARISHA: With our shit all fucked up?

02:45:57.037 --> 02:46:00.966
MATT: Yeah, it would take a shorter time. It's
about eight days or so to get there, eyeballing it

02:46:00.966 --> 02:46:06.432
from here, I'd say. More than that, ten days.

02:46:06.432 --> 02:46:10.741
LAURA: Can we cast Control Water to get us there
faster at all?

02:46:10.741 --> 02:46:12.362
MATT: Do you have access to Control Water?

02:46:12.362 --> 02:46:13.557
LAURA: Of course I do.

02:46:13.557 --> 02:46:14.581
TRAVIS and LIAM: You do?

02:46:14.581 --> 02:46:15.787
MATT: Then yeah.

02:46:15.787 --> 02:46:17.002
LIAM: Oh fuck.

02:46:17.002 --> 02:46:18.651
LAURA: Maybe I can do that every day.

02:46:18.651 --> 02:46:20.930
MATT: Okay. I'll say, with the Control Water--

02:46:20.930 --> 02:46:22.641
TRAVIS: Fucking secrets.

02:46:22.641 --> 02:46:25.824
TALIESIN: I was about to say, I might be able to
do that too.

02:46:26.172 --> 02:46:31.150
SAM: Come on, everyone has Control Water, don't
they? I've got it.

02:46:31.150 --> 02:46:38.648
LIAM: I've been waiting to drop it. Fucking water
genasi heritage, man.

02:46:38.648 --> 02:46:41.956
TALIESIN: Nope, never mind-- oh, yeah, I've got
it, too.

02:46:41.956 --> 02:46:43.320
MATT: It's in the cleric list, yeah.

02:46:43.320 --> 02:46:48.201
MARISHA: It's a cleric-- oh god! d4 just went
flying!

02:46:49.149 --> 02:46:53.868
MATT: Between the two of you, it allows you a
brief moment where you can actually surge the

02:46:53.868 --> 02:47:03.110
water and grant you a speed boost. I'd say that'll
cut three days off of your travel-- the two of

02:47:03.110 --> 02:47:08.242
you, each day, spending that slot to push it. It's
like a speedboat burst. All of a sudden, your

02:47:08.242 --> 02:47:16.012
giant, three-mast ship is going (crashing water),
speedboating across the ocean briefly.

02:47:16.012 --> 02:47:22.239
MARISHA: Is it an event each day? Does the crew
come out and we all join. Like, "Yeah!"

02:47:22.239 --> 02:47:24.539
TALIESIN: It's like in Mary Poppins; everyone
holds the china.

02:47:24.539 --> 02:47:25.644
MARISHA: Exactly!

02:47:25.644 --> 02:47:27.288
TALIESIN: And 12 o'clock.

02:47:27.288 --> 02:47:29.219
MARISHA: And let's go.

02:47:29.219 --> 02:47:31.696
LIAM: You're so stupid, Rose.

02:47:31.696 --> 02:47:37.789
MATT: Eventually, you make your way to the open
waters in the vicinity of-- Orly goes with you

02:47:37.789 --> 02:47:42.789
each day and looks about and gives you the
once-over and goes, "I'm pretty sure that we're

02:47:42.789 --> 02:47:46.433
"pretty dang close to that place you were asking
about."

02:47:46.433 --> 02:47:52.450
TRAVIS: I appreciate that, Orly. Hey, Caduceus, do
you have any way of, I don't know-- you've got

02:47:52.450 --> 02:47:58.362
those vibes, right?-- feeling down and, I don't
know, doing a little ping on the bottom?

02:47:58.430 --> 02:48:01.294
TALIESIN: What do you-- I don't entirely
understand what you're--

02:48:01.294 --> 02:48:05.039
TRAVIS: I don't know, I don't want to put you in a
box or anything, but you seem to pick up the most.

02:48:05.039 --> 02:48:12.543
TALIESIN: You want to see if I get-- oh, for the
ship. I don't know. That's a--

02:48:13.017 --> 02:48:15.500
LAURA: That'd be a Locate Object sort of
situation?

02:48:15.500 --> 02:48:27.094
TALIESIN: I've got Locate Creature. Yeah, we've
both got Locate Object, so we can both help with that.

02:48:27.094 --> 02:48:28.332
SAM: What object?

02:48:28.332 --> 02:48:29.607
LAURA: A ship.

02:48:29.607 --> 02:48:35.921
TRAVIS: I'll summon the falchion and I'll say:
Maybe try to locate this, and I'll point towards

02:48:35.921 --> 02:48:41.003
the eye. Not this eye, but a similar eye.

02:48:41.003 --> 02:48:42.296
LIAM: Do you mean your penis?

02:48:42.296 --> 02:48:43.478
TRAVIS: Nope.

02:48:43.478 --> 02:48:45.411
LAURA: I'm going to do it.

02:48:45.411 --> 02:48:52.038
MATT: Okay. It's a thousand-foot range, and it has
to be something familiar to you.

02:48:52.038 --> 02:48:56.328
TALIESIN: I'm looking for a boat. I'm looking for
a ship. I'm looking for a shipwreck, not an

02:48:56.328 --> 02:48:58.389
object. We could do object, too.

02:48:58.389 --> 02:49:00.415
LAURA: Yeah, I'm going to look for his.

02:49:00.415 --> 02:49:07.094
MATT: Okay. That's 2nd-level? It lasts for ten
minutes.

02:49:07.094 --> 02:49:09.460
TALIESIN: So we can take turns.

02:49:09.460 --> 02:49:11.977
MATT: Okay, and how many spell slots do you have
2nd-level each?

02:49:11.977 --> 02:49:13.152
LAURA: Three each.

02:49:13.152 --> 02:49:23.801
MATT: So if you're both trading off, it's about
three chances per type of use per day. How many

02:49:23.801 --> 02:49:27.459
days you want to spend looking total?

02:49:27.459 --> 02:49:28.875
MARISHA: For the boat?

02:49:28.875 --> 02:49:29.889
MATT: Yeah.

02:49:29.889 --> 02:49:31.258
TRAVIS: How long do we have?

02:49:31.258 --> 02:49:32.594
MATT: It's up to you.

02:49:32.594 --> 02:49:34.589
SAM: Do we have unlimited supplies?

02:49:34.589 --> 02:49:36.868
MATT: Well, these guys can summon stuff with
magic, if I recall.

02:49:36.868 --> 02:49:42.642
TALIESIN: Yeah, so the food ain't good, but it's
edible and the water's fine.

02:49:42.642 --> 02:49:46.782
MARISHA: Until we find it.

02:49:46.782 --> 02:49:53.329
TRAVIS: Yeah? What, like two days and then go fix
the boat proper and come back if we have to?

02:49:54.310 --> 02:49:57.196
MARISHA: I don't know. Maybe that's a team
discussion.

02:49:57.618 --> 02:50:02.158
TRAVIS: How about we spend two to three days, and
if we don't find it, we can go and repair the boat

02:50:02.158 --> 02:50:04.328
proper or at least get the materials to do that?

02:50:04.328 --> 02:50:08.723
TALIESIN: We can cast it at level three also,
which is another--

02:50:08.723 --> 02:50:17.061
SAM: If we find it, though, and we go down there--
we can't go down there. Can we go down there?

02:50:17.061 --> 02:50:19.315
TRAVIS: Sure we can.

02:50:19.315 --> 02:50:21.905
SAM: But then we can't make a hasty retreat.

02:50:21.905 --> 02:50:25.709
LAURA: Yeah, it might be smart to have a boat that
actually works before we go down.

02:50:25.709 --> 02:50:28.123
SAM: I guess we could do a recon first.

02:50:28.123 --> 02:50:32.503
MARISHA: There still begs the question of, is
someone else going to come looking for this? Now

02:50:32.503 --> 02:50:33.853
that the Plank King--

02:50:33.853 --> 02:50:35.737
TALIESIN: I like that we're here now.

02:50:35.737 --> 02:50:41.899
MARISHA: We gave the book with the cipher over, so
if anybody else wants it--

02:50:41.899 --> 02:50:44.055
LAURA: Yeah, but we ripped out the page saying
where to find--

02:50:44.055 --> 02:50:49.083
MARISHA: We did! Oh my god!

02:50:49.083 --> 02:50:52.229
LIAM: All the pertinent information is also in
here.

02:50:52.229 --> 02:50:57.979
TRAVIS: Nott, I would leave it at your discretion.
We all have the ability to travel under the waves

02:50:57.979 --> 02:51:00.449
with great ease.

02:51:00.449 --> 02:51:05.382
SAM: We do? How? I don't.

02:51:05.382 --> 02:51:11.118
TRAVIS: I have a way of making it so that water
becomes like air for you down there.

02:51:11.118 --> 02:51:15.926
SAM: Does it feel like water?

02:51:15.926 --> 02:51:22.107
TRAVIS: It feels a little thicker, like if you
were in a really dense fog, maybe?

02:51:22.107 --> 02:51:24.269
SAM: But it's still water?

02:51:24.269 --> 02:51:25.763
TRAVIS: It is.

02:51:25.763 --> 02:51:31.657
LAURA: But you can breathe it, so it's really
not.

02:51:31.657 --> 02:51:36.086
TRAVIS: Or you could stay above if you wanted to
send a Message if some trouble appears on the

02:51:36.086 --> 02:51:40.679
horizon, I'd just hate to leave you behind on such
a great adventure. There could be buttons, there

02:51:40.679 --> 02:51:43.842
could be little jewels, ingots--

02:51:43.842 --> 02:51:48.201
SAM: Don't you talk down to me. I know what you're
up to.

02:51:48.201 --> 02:51:51.148
TRAVIS: What are you talking about? Iit's the
bottom of the ocean. Ships throw people all the time.

02:51:51.148 --> 02:51:54.938
LIAM: Full disclosure, I could help you cope
with--

02:51:54.938 --> 02:51:57.959
SAM: He thinks I'm going to go into the water for
some fucking buttons.

02:51:57.959 --> 02:52:02.513
TRAVIS: I heard tell there was a button ship that
crashed right along the water.

02:52:02.513 --> 02:52:10.634
SAM: Oh, the old button ship legend, really?! Oh!
Buttonbeard the Pirate?!

02:52:10.634 --> 02:52:11.408
TRAVIS: Yep.

02:52:11.408 --> 02:52:14.075
SAM: He had buttons for beards!

02:52:14.075 --> 02:52:21.506
LIAM: Nott the Brave. We have things to accomplish
here. If you allow me, I could do what I have done

02:52:21.506 --> 02:52:28.961
in the past a little sneakily to help you cope
with this fear you have. If you allow me.

02:52:28.961 --> 02:52:35.704
SAM: I appreciate that, Caleb, but I've got my own
way of doing it.

02:52:35.704 --> 02:52:39.407
LIAM: Is it Mike Myers?

02:52:39.612 --> 02:52:43.877
TRAVIS: There might be bronzed shoes, maybe little
silver cups. Decoder rings.

02:52:43.877 --> 02:52:50.800
SAM: Ooh, those spoons? The little spoons, the
collectible ones? Fuck this guy.

02:52:51.890 --> 02:52:57.620
LIAM: We're not there yet, though, we're talking
in advance at this point? All in advance?

02:52:57.620 --> 02:52:58.462
LAURA: Yeah.

02:52:58.462 --> 02:53:00.322
TRAVIS: We're coming upon the area, right?

02:53:00.322 --> 02:53:09.479
MATT: Altogether with the eight of them, it cuts
the travel time down to five days. So you've got time.

02:53:09.479 --> 02:53:11.725
SAM: I'll think about it.

02:53:11.725 --> 02:53:15.844
TALIESIN: I'm going to be stocking us up on food
too, so that there's more than enough food and

02:53:15.844 --> 02:53:17.457
water for the whole group.

02:53:17.457 --> 02:53:26.349
SAM: Pewter? Plates? Those little collectible
plates from the Stanford Mint or whatever?

02:53:26.349 --> 02:53:30.721
LAURA: So we're going to hang around this area
before we get to the boat wrecks, yeah?

02:53:30.721 --> 02:53:32.406
TRAVIS: Yeah, I think so.

02:53:32.406 --> 02:53:33.396
LAURA: Okay.

02:53:33.396 --> 02:53:41.958
MATT: Okay, so taking your time, I would like you
to each to roll a base wisdom check for each pass

02:53:41.958 --> 02:53:44.987
as you go through.

02:53:44.987 --> 02:53:47.444
SAM: You two, right?

02:53:47.444 --> 02:53:51.370
MATT: Yes. d20 plus your wisdom modifier.

02:53:51.370 --> 02:53:53.002
TALIESIN: 19.

02:53:53.002 --> 02:53:54.102
LAURA: 12.

02:53:54.102 --> 02:53:56.201
MATT: Okay. Again.

02:53:58.630 --> 02:54:01.437
LAURA: God. Nine.

02:54:01.437 --> 02:54:05.515
TALIESIN: Oh, I'm doing save. I'm so sorry. Fuck,
I was doing the wrong--

02:54:05.515 --> 02:54:06.867
LAURA: Oh, shit! I was, too.

02:54:06.867 --> 02:54:08.561
MATT: This is just check. Add your wisdom
modifier.

02:54:08.561 --> 02:54:10.294
LAURA: Even lower.

02:54:10.294 --> 02:54:17.299
TALIESIN: I said 19? 16, and then 19.

02:54:17.299 --> 02:54:25.081
MATT: Okay. Roll again. Your third spell slot of
the first day, hitting this space and scanning the load.

02:54:25.688 --> 02:54:26.653
LAURA: 15.

02:54:26.653 --> 02:54:28.076
TALIESIN: 14.

02:54:28.489 --> 02:54:36.027
MATT: Okay, and you're utilizing your memory of
passage through here, as well as Orly's direction

02:54:36.027 --> 02:54:43.444
on this ocean. Go ahead and roll an intelligence
check for me.

02:54:48.137 --> 02:54:49.723
TRAVIS: 13.

02:54:49.723 --> 02:54:58.866
MATT: Okay. First day goes through. Nothing
catches your attention. You pass around, and then

02:54:58.866 --> 02:55:04.580
once you make it quite past the area, based on the
measurements, where you think that you recall it

02:55:04.580 --> 02:55:11.416
happening. The next day, you make a curved turn
and begin to head out to see some more land, as

02:55:11.416 --> 02:55:19.117
you can, to widen the perspective of your search.
For the second day, roll again.

02:55:20.676 --> 02:55:22.376
TALIESIN: Three?

02:55:22.376 --> 02:55:26.448
MATT: Three in a row, yeah. Unless you want to use
more spell slots to do more. So you can do your

02:55:26.448 --> 02:55:28.298
3rd-level to burn as well.

02:55:28.298 --> 02:55:31.109
LAURA: That's true. 20 on the first roll.

02:55:31.109 --> 02:55:33.596
TALIESIN: 20 on the first roll.

02:55:34.800 --> 02:55:36.454
LAURA: Lame on the second roll.

02:55:36.454 --> 02:55:38.219
TALIESIN: 14 on the second roll.

02:55:38.219 --> 02:55:42.501
MATT: (sneezes) Pardon me. Thank you. (sneezes)
Pardon. Thank you.

02:55:42.501 --> 02:55:44.138
SAM: You're a three-sneezer?

02:55:44.138 --> 02:55:46.241
MATT: I am, at least.

02:55:46.241 --> 02:55:47.971
LAURA: Should we try one more?

02:55:47.971 --> 02:55:51.771
TALIESIN: 16, 19. Yeah, let's blow another. What
else are we going to do for the day?

02:55:51.771 --> 02:55:52.547
MATT: Sure.

02:55:52.547 --> 02:55:55.662
LAURA: Motherfuck!

02:55:56.052 --> 02:55:57.407
TALIESIN: 24.

02:55:57.407 --> 02:55:58.658
LAURA: Six.

02:55:58.658 --> 02:56:01.247
MATT: Go ahead and roll an intelligence check for
you as well.

02:56:01.247 --> 02:56:02.859
MARISHA: Come on!

02:56:02.859 --> 02:56:04.714
LIAM: "Fuh-jord-y!"

02:56:05.237 --> 02:56:06.474
TRAVIS: 11.

02:56:06.474 --> 02:56:21.845
MATT: Okay. You go through the second day, and
towards the end, you, Caduceus, sense a brief

02:56:21.845 --> 02:56:29.163
moment where something ship-related catches your
attention, and then is gone.

02:56:29.163 --> 02:56:31.448
TALIESIN: I had a moment.

02:56:31.448 --> 02:56:32.439
TRAVIS: You did?

02:56:32.439 --> 02:56:36.060
TALIESIN: Yeah. It's gone now. Would I know
direction, even?

02:56:36.060 --> 02:56:38.193
MATT: Vague direction.

02:56:38.193 --> 02:56:39.364
TALIESIN: But we're moving, I know.

02:56:39.364 --> 02:56:42.097
MATT: Yeah, you're moving. So it's like, all
right, let's go ahead and turn it around.

02:56:42.097 --> 02:56:44.658
SAM: Just point. Caleb will know the direction.

02:56:44.658 --> 02:56:49.668
MATT: You turn the ship back in the direction of
where it goes. At the very end of the second day,

02:56:49.668 --> 02:56:57.954
just as dusk is starting to creep in, you make
your way back in the area, and you sense another hit.

02:56:57.954 --> 02:57:02.326
LAURA: Ooh. Should I use another 3rd-level spell
and try to find the orb-y thing?

02:57:02.326 --> 02:57:04.789
TALIESIN: Let's do one more.

02:57:04.789 --> 02:57:10.250
MATT: Okay. As you're attempting to find the orb,
roll a wisdom check.

02:57:10.250 --> 02:57:14.206
TALIESIN: I'll also join in for one more for that
as well. It's my last spell slot.

02:57:14.206 --> 02:57:16.888
MATT: Okay. You lose your concentration on the
Locate Object.

02:57:16.888 --> 02:57:21.986
TALIESIN: Oh. Okay, I'm still holding the boat.
That's fine.

02:57:21.986 --> 02:57:28.328
MATT: You circle around again. You've closed off a
distance, but you haven't quite located the

02:57:28.328 --> 02:57:33.324
specific area yet. You're trying to guide into a
vicinity. I mean, it's hard to really remember

02:57:33.324 --> 02:57:38.744
specifically where, when it's just open water and
a storm looming, especially. So you get to a

02:57:38.744 --> 02:57:42.200
certain point where you're like, I'm not sure I'm
being able to help, but you're starting to get

02:57:42.200 --> 02:57:47.470
something. You're not entirely sure. The
divination seems to be helping, or this aspect of

02:57:47.470 --> 02:57:56.051
your Locate spell. Evening comes to a close. You
ride the night out. The clouds are still thick.

02:57:56.051 --> 02:58:02.437
The next morning, you can attempt again if you
like, both of you.

02:58:02.437 --> 02:58:05.021
TRAVIS: Come on, you got it.

02:58:05.021 --> 02:58:07.360
SAM: Bless or something. Do a Bless!

02:58:07.360 --> 02:58:09.189
LAURA: I don't have Bless!

02:58:09.189 --> 02:58:10.296
SAM: No, he does.

02:58:10.296 --> 02:58:11.101
TALIESIN: I do.

02:58:11.101 --> 02:58:12.124
LAURA: Bless us!

02:58:12.124 --> 02:58:13.730
MATT: Make another intelligence check for me as
well.

02:58:13.730 --> 02:58:15.268
TALIESIN: Actually, this is a check, not a save,
so it wouldn't--

02:58:15.268 --> 02:58:21.893
LAURA: Oh, and I want to learn the cantrip
Guidance, but I don't know any good healers that

02:58:21.893 --> 02:58:24.169
can teach it to me.

02:58:24.169 --> 02:58:26.429
MARISHA: Druids can teach it, too.

02:58:27.126 --> 02:58:28.005
LAURA: 18.

02:58:28.005 --> 02:58:29.008
TALIESIN: 15.

02:58:29.008 --> 02:58:30.033
TRAVIS: 20.

02:58:30.033 --> 02:58:33.621
MATT: Okay. Roll again.

02:58:33.621 --> 02:58:36.168
SAM: One last one.

02:58:36.168 --> 02:58:37.789
MATT: This is your second spell slot used
today?

02:58:37.789 --> 02:58:38.818
TALIESIN: 19.

02:58:38.818 --> 02:58:40.645
LAURA: Motherfuck. I'm going to use a third.

02:58:40.645 --> 02:58:41.944
TALIESIN: That was my third, was 19.

02:58:41.944 --> 02:58:45.680
MATT: Okay.

02:58:45.680 --> 02:58:47.792
LAURA: 21.

02:58:47.792 --> 02:58:52.527
MATT: Okay. Between the 21 and your 20 intellect
in guiding the ship around, you find yourself now

02:58:52.527 --> 02:58:57.118
collecting a secondary blip. Once again, on the
ship, not on the eye.

02:58:57.118 --> 02:58:58.413
LAURA: I was on the orb.

02:58:58.413 --> 02:59:00.082
MATT: You're concentrating on the orb, or the
ship?

02:59:00.082 --> 02:59:01.460
LAURA: I was concentrating on the ball.

02:59:01.460 --> 02:59:04.213
MATT: The ball? You find nothing.

02:59:04.213 --> 02:59:12.608
TRAVIS: I think that means it's probably not down
there, but I'd still like to take a look.

02:59:12.608 --> 02:59:14.753
LIAM: Are we close? What are you telling us?

02:59:14.753 --> 02:59:19.208
TRAVIS: I think so. We're starting to round an
area that I think we could probably fan out and

02:59:19.208 --> 02:59:22.588
explore amongst the seven of us.

02:59:22.798 --> 02:59:34.808
LIAM: I just got my cat back, but if you want an
octopus to look on the bottom, you have it.

02:59:34.808 --> 02:59:36.249
TALIESIN: That's a very good idea.

02:59:36.249 --> 02:59:40.487
TRAVIS: That is, actually. If it wouldn't be too
much trouble, Caleb, that would be--

02:59:40.487 --> 02:59:48.904
LIAM: Yeah, I have just enough incense to-- yeah
sure, let's make an octopus. Cat-shaped. An

02:59:48.904 --> 02:59:50.773
octopus-shaped cat.

02:59:50.773 --> 02:59:54.105
MARISHA: Oh wow. How far does your octopus'
connection go for?

02:59:54.105 --> 02:59:58.679
LIAM: Well, I can tell him to go look and he'll
come back to me. I can see through him for--

02:59:58.679 --> 03:00:01.045
MARISHA: Yeah, but how far is your connection?

03:00:01.045 --> 03:00:09.884
LIAM: It's a thousand feet. To watch, but he can
go and come back, and I trust him. He's Frumpkin.

03:00:09.884 --> 03:00:18.065
I pull out my book and I set it on the deck and I
start working on turning my cat into an octopus.

03:00:18.065 --> 03:00:20.551
SAM: Does this mean we don't have to go in the
water?

03:00:20.551 --> 03:00:22.943
TALIESIN: Oh, this means we'll probably have to go
in the water.

03:00:22.943 --> 03:00:25.715
SAM: What? Why? He's got an octopus.

03:00:25.715 --> 03:00:29.564
LIAM: An hour later, an octopus pops out, if we
wait that long.

03:00:29.564 --> 03:00:31.637
TRAVIS: Yeah, I'd be okay with it.

03:00:31.637 --> 03:00:33.268
MATT: So you create a Frumpkin octopus.

03:00:33.268 --> 03:00:40.379
LIAM: Yeah. (sighs) Well, we had one or two days
together. Just throw him off.

03:00:40.379 --> 03:00:46.407
MATT: (splashing) Frumpkin makes his way in the
darkness.

03:00:46.407 --> 03:00:50.128
TALIESIN: I'm also going to put Bless on the
octopus before it.

03:00:50.128 --> 03:00:52.071
MATT: Okay. How long does it last?

03:00:52.071 --> 03:00:57.000
TALIESIN: It's one minute.

03:00:57.000 --> 03:01:04.153
LIAM: So I'll watch for the first thousand feet,
but I assume he goes beyond that, because it's the

03:01:04.153 --> 03:01:11.814
ocean, so he keeps going down and down and down. I
will tell him to look for this wreck, for what we

03:01:11.814 --> 03:01:15.163
are looking for, and when he finds it to come back
and tell me about it.

03:01:15.163 --> 03:01:17.613
MATT: Okay. Make a perception check for Frumpkin.

03:01:21.313 --> 03:01:22.533
LIAM: 13.

03:01:22.533 --> 03:01:31.216
MATT: Okay. About an hour goes by. Nothing. Roll
again.

03:01:34.454 --> 03:01:35.976
LIAM: 17.

03:01:35.976 --> 03:01:44.812
MATT: Frumpkin goes beyond your visual range for a
bit. You start getting worried, and then Frumpkin

03:01:44.812 --> 03:01:50.460
returns and is making his way quickly towards the
ship.

03:01:50.460 --> 03:01:52.895
LIAM: If he's within 1000, we have a connection.

03:01:52.895 --> 03:01:54.172
MATT: 100-foot is the connection.

03:01:54.172 --> 03:01:55.273
LIAM: A hundred? Thank you.

03:01:55.273 --> 03:01:58.232
MARISHA: Maybe he'll see Dashilla.

03:01:58.232 --> 03:01:59.598
LIAM: Maybe it's 10,000.

03:01:59.598 --> 03:02:04.748
MATT: Technically, the distance doesn't matter for
what you can see through his eyes. It's a 100 feet

03:02:04.748 --> 03:02:05.885
for it to communicate.

03:02:05.885 --> 03:02:09.775
LIAM: Right, we've established that. I can see
indefinitely. That's what we established early in

03:02:09.775 --> 03:02:13.447
the campaign with the circus, but I can't
communicate with him.

03:02:13.447 --> 03:02:18.538
MATT: Correct, during that time. So yeah, you
watch through Frumpkin's eyes as he makes his way

03:02:18.538 --> 03:02:29.436
toward the-- finally finding the floor of this
ocean. Over this second hour of his search, he

03:02:29.436 --> 03:02:36.280
catches one shape that is emerging like an obelisk
on the bottom of the ocean. Upon getting close

03:02:36.280 --> 03:02:46.645
enough, you can see it looks to be the front of a
wrecked ship, itself damaged and caked in

03:02:46.645 --> 03:02:56.233
minerals, ocean floor plant life, barnacles. It
appears to be a damaged ship.

03:02:59.503 --> 03:03:01.659
SAM: Does it have a name?

03:03:01.722 --> 03:03:03.564
LIAM: I don't hear any of you.

03:03:03.564 --> 03:03:05.527
SAM: (shouting) Does it have a name?

03:03:05.527 --> 03:03:08.052
MARISHA: You're in my ear. Ow!

03:03:08.052 --> 03:03:10.195
SAM: Sorry.

03:03:10.195 --> 03:03:15.580
LIAM: Ooh, he has found the ship. This is a
reminder I can't hear any of you. I don't want to

03:03:15.580 --> 03:03:19.786
disconnect. Don't give me wet willies.

03:03:19.786 --> 03:03:21.717
LAURA: I give him a wet willie.

03:03:21.717 --> 03:03:25.107
SAM: Six wet willies.

03:03:25.107 --> 03:03:27.838
TRAVIS: His ears are just dripping saliva.

03:03:27.838 --> 03:03:30.925
MATT and LAURA: (groaning)

03:03:30.925 --> 03:03:37.332
MATT: Okay. Frumpkin does a circle on it, before
feeling confident that he's discovered at least

03:03:37.332 --> 03:03:44.064
something of interest, and then beelines it back
to the Squalleater.

03:03:44.064 --> 03:03:51.081
LIAM: Who's a good boy?! You are the best cat that
was ever put on this planet!

03:03:51.081 --> 03:03:54.182
MATT: Then Frumpkin is now there at the surface of
the water, without really a way getting back into

03:03:54.182 --> 03:03:55.330
the ship.

03:03:55.330 --> 03:03:57.077
LIAM: Oh yeah?

03:03:57.077 --> 03:03:58.850
MATT: Yeah, there you go, back in your shoulder.

03:03:58.850 --> 03:04:05.626
LIAM: Oh, come here you. You are the most
important member of this team and don't let

03:04:05.626 --> 03:04:10.036
Beauregard tell you different. Or Nott.

03:04:10.036 --> 03:04:14.200
MARISHA: Do you ever feel like your relationship
with your cat is hindering building stronger

03:04:14.200 --> 03:04:16.491
relationships with human people?

03:04:16.491 --> 03:04:18.204
SAM: I've told him that a lot of times.

03:04:18.204 --> 03:04:22.084
MARISHA: I feel concerned about you sometimes.

03:04:22.226 --> 03:04:25.310
LIAM: Yeah, that is so silly, isn't it? Silly, yes
it is.

03:04:25.310 --> 03:04:27.916
SAM: Tell us what he found!

03:04:27.916 --> 03:04:34.595
LIAM: He found the boat, Nott. he found the boat. He will
lead us to the boat. He found it. He did it.

03:04:34.595 --> 03:04:35.976
SAM: That's great.

03:04:35.976 --> 03:04:43.483
TRAVIS: That is great news. Does anybody not
want to join? Really? You want to stay up here?

03:04:43.483 --> 03:04:46.332
SAM: How far down is it?

03:04:46.332 --> 03:04:48.103
LIAM: It's the bottom of the ocean.

03:04:48.103 --> 03:04:49.515
SAM: And how far is that?

03:04:49.515 --> 03:04:51.454
LIAM: It's thousands of feet.

03:04:51.454 --> 03:04:52.940
LAURA: No, it wasn't a thousand.

03:04:52.940 --> 03:04:54.502
LIAM: Thousands of feet.

03:04:54.502 --> 03:04:56.629
MATT: Over an hour.

03:04:56.629 --> 03:04:59.812
SAM: Ugh, fuck that. No way!

03:04:59.812 --> 03:05:05.408
MATT: Like, just barely. From the distance where
you are now. It'd be just under a thousand if you

03:05:05.408 --> 03:05:10.892
were right over, but you're not entirely certain
how far. The boat isn't set for that currently.

03:05:10.892 --> 03:05:12.823
LIAM: You have a method to bring us down there.

03:05:12.823 --> 03:05:13.750
SAM: What is this method?

03:05:13.750 --> 03:05:16.432
LIAM: Describe it to me. I've read a bit. Explain
it to the goblin.

03:05:16.432 --> 03:05:23.423
TRAVIS: I'll cast a little-- on you and for 24
hours, you can breathe underwater freely.

03:05:23.423 --> 03:05:24.835
LIAM: That is a whole day.

03:05:24.835 --> 03:05:27.173
SAM: But you still have to move through the water,
you still have to swim through it--

03:05:27.173 --> 03:05:30.501
TRAVIS: Yeah. You could hold onto my shoulders if
you wanted to.

03:05:30.501 --> 03:05:33.380
MARISHA: Could we give ourselves some weights to
get us down there?

03:05:33.380 --> 03:05:35.542
MATT: You've got weight.

03:05:35.542 --> 03:05:37.994
MARISHA: Concrete shoes!

03:05:37.994 --> 03:05:40.671
SAM: Sounds terrifying.

03:05:40.671 --> 03:05:43.141
TRAVIS: Actually, we could take a few of the
cannonballs to just--

03:05:43.141 --> 03:05:44.891
MARISHA: We should have weights that weigh us down
there.

03:05:44.891 --> 03:05:50.044
LAURA: Will the breathing underwater, will that
make it to where our ears won't hurt really bad?

03:05:50.044 --> 03:05:53.357
Because I hear when you go down underwater, your
ears hurt really bad.

03:05:53.357 --> 03:05:55.554
TRAVIS: That's because of the air. You're going to
have to equalize.

03:05:55.554 --> 03:05:57.292
SAM: Your ears hurt bad too? Jesus.

03:05:57.292 --> 03:06:00.376
TRAVIS: But if you're breathing water, there's no
air to expand or contract.

03:06:00.376 --> 03:06:04.575
MARISHA: Won't you crush under the pressure of the
water after a certain point?.

03:06:04.575 --> 03:06:08.531
TRAVIS: After a certain depth. There's only one
way to find out.

03:06:08.531 --> 03:06:14.569
LIAM: Now, you people have not read about-- you
don't understand magic. It's not like that. I want

03:06:14.569 --> 03:06:16.230
to try this.

03:06:16.230 --> 03:06:22.098
TRAVIS: I know. I do, too. Those that want to
join, join me at the rail. I'll jump on and sit on the rail.

03:06:22.098 --> 03:06:25.307
LAURA: No, wait! We have to get a good night's
sleep. We just used all of our spells finding this shit!

03:06:25.307 --> 03:06:28.783
MARISHA: Oh yeah. That's a good point.

03:06:28.783 --> 03:06:33.458
TALIESIN: Let's have them. Let's tell the crew
what's up. Early in the morning, at first light.

03:06:33.458 --> 03:06:36.605
LIAM: It's too late. Fjord's in the water,
swimming around.

03:06:36.605 --> 03:06:37.879
MARISHA: Caduceus, you making breakfast?

03:06:37.879 --> 03:06:41.581
TALIESIN: I'm always making breakfast. I'm not
going to even use the weird plants.

03:06:41.581 --> 03:06:43.701
MARISHA: I'll get up for Caduceus' breakfast.

03:06:43.701 --> 03:06:47.445
TALIESIN: I've been putting that weird fruit in
everyone's food for a week now, by the way. Just

03:06:47.445 --> 03:06:48.947
so we're clear.

03:06:48.947 --> 03:06:50.263
LIAM: In minimal amounts, or full dose?

03:06:50.263 --> 03:06:51.549
MATT: The stuff that you found at Urukayxl?

03:06:51.549 --> 03:06:52.970
TALIESIN: Just kidding, but wouldn't that be
great?

03:06:52.970 --> 03:06:54.046
MATT: That would be amazing

03:06:54.046 --> 03:06:55.871
TALIESIN: Everyone's just be like, "Wow!"

03:06:55.871 --> 03:07:01.132
LIAM: There was no battle. There was no battle
with Avantika, man!

03:07:01.132 --> 03:07:03.462
TRAVIS: We're not on the boat, we're in sand.

03:07:03.462 --> 03:07:04.858
LAURA: There's no nothing.

03:07:04.858 --> 03:07:08.990
LIAM: We're sitting in your mom's sitting room
right now.

03:07:08.990 --> 03:07:13.661
MATT: You look up and on the side, there's the
Plank King and Avantika looking at him. He's like,

03:07:13.661 --> 03:07:15.318
"Where you'd find these people?"

03:07:15.318 --> 03:07:19.540
(laughter)

03:07:19.540 --> 03:07:26.674
MATT: All right, so you guys have another night's
rest. As you wake up the next morning, it is

03:07:26.674 --> 03:07:32.719
raining. There appears to be a small storm making
its way in there.

03:07:32.719 --> 03:07:37.136
MARISHA: Are the fish out? Fish always come out
when it rains.

03:07:37.136 --> 03:07:46.817
MATT: Well, once you make it in the ocean, you'll
find out. Noticeably, Yasha is energized with the

03:07:46.817 --> 03:07:54.664
coming of the storm. Seems to be in more energetic
spirits than you're used to seeing her. You guys

03:07:54.664 --> 03:07:59.044
complete your meal for breakfast. You gather your
supplies. What are you going to do?

03:07:59.044 --> 03:08:04.715
TRAVIS: I'll leave Orly in command while we head
under. To complete this spell, I'm going to need

03:08:04.715 --> 03:08:07.634
everyone to hold hands in a circle.

03:08:07.634 --> 03:08:15.734
MARISHA: I would like to sing a little Kumbaya
song and refresh everybody on the Diver's Grave,

03:08:15.734 --> 03:08:18.303
which is where we are.

03:08:18.303 --> 03:08:19.790
SAM: Are you going to sing that Diver's Grave
song?

03:08:19.790 --> 03:08:22.907
MARISHA: (singing) Kumbaya, the cursed woman--

03:08:22.907 --> 03:08:24.980
LAURA: (singing) Dashilla the Dreadful--

03:08:24.980 --> 03:08:30.119
MARISHA: (singing) Kumbaya Dashilla, Dashilla with
claws that grasp.

03:08:30.119 --> 03:08:32.193
TRAVIS: Do we need to have the rights to that
song?

03:08:32.193 --> 03:08:34.240
MARISHA: (singing) Oh god I hope not.

03:08:34.240 --> 03:08:35.719
LAURA: (singing) And a hungry eye.

03:08:35.719 --> 03:08:40.948
MARISHA: (singing) She's got a hungry eye and with
a lantern light. Dashilla, the cursed woman,

03:08:40.948 --> 03:08:43.310
treasures in her eyes.

03:08:43.310 --> 03:08:44.727
SAM: This is nice.

03:08:44.727 --> 03:08:46.002
TRAVIS: Uh-huh. Cool.

03:08:46.002 --> 03:08:47.802
MARISHA: (singing) Dashilla the cursed.

03:08:47.802 --> 03:08:49.746
LIAM: I am casting Mage Armor during whatever the
fuck this is.

03:08:49.746 --> 03:08:50.378
MATT: Okay.

03:08:50.378 --> 03:08:51.504
SAM: That was good.

03:08:51.504 --> 03:08:52.624
MARISHA: I'm just saying.

03:08:52.624 --> 03:08:56.568
LAURA: Did you give us anything for that? Did we
get bonuses or did we just get to hear you sing?

03:08:56.568 --> 03:08:59.533
MARISHA: No, that was Keyleth. Sorry.

03:08:59.533 --> 03:09:02.174
LAURA: It was literally just Beau singing.

03:09:02.174 --> 03:09:04.131
MARISHA: Just me trying to do--

03:09:04.131 --> 03:09:07.007
TRAVIS: Well, while it's happening, because it was
such a good song, I will cast Underwater Breathing

03:09:07.007 --> 03:09:09.651
on all seven of us.

03:09:09.651 --> 03:09:13.367
MARISHA: My song was that good.

03:09:13.367 --> 03:09:18.013
MATT: All right, all of you now have the
capability for the next 24 hours to breathe

03:09:18.013 --> 03:09:24.581
underwater. Your lungs feel heavier than they do
while you breathe air. It's unique. No gills

03:09:24.581 --> 03:09:30.688
sprout from the side of your neck, per se, but the
air itself seems to have a weight to it, and

03:09:30.688 --> 03:09:36.340
you're like (exhales). It's still breathable air,
but the process seems to have changed a bit.

03:09:36.340 --> 03:09:37.689
LIAM: It's the abyss.

03:09:37.689 --> 03:09:45.028
MARISHA: In preparation for this, I went and I
gathered a few sandbags. Took some burlap, filled

03:09:45.028 --> 03:09:47.085
them with--

03:09:47.085 --> 03:09:49.259
MATT: There's no sand to fill them with out in the
ocean, unfortunately.

03:09:49.259 --> 03:09:50.562
MARISHA: Uh-huh.

03:09:50.562 --> 03:09:51.800
TRAVIS: Cannonballs?

03:09:51.800 --> 03:09:54.612
MARISHA: Okay, yeah sure. I got the
eight-pounders.

03:09:54.612 --> 03:09:56.102
SAM: You have to clear that with me.

03:09:56.102 --> 03:09:59.612
MARISHA: I brought out a few-- but look, I'm the
barrel person.

03:09:59.612 --> 03:10:05.704
MATT: As a note, too, when the Squalleater came to
port that night, Darktow was resupplied with

03:10:05.704 --> 03:10:09.939
cannonballs on board. For those who are keeping
track, which would be--

03:10:09.939 --> 03:10:10.975
SAM: Me!

03:10:10.975 --> 03:10:17.522
MATT: You. The ship currently has a cache of 30
cannonballs.

03:10:17.522 --> 03:10:21.118
SAM: Nice. How many are you taking?

03:10:21.118 --> 03:10:25.518
TRAVIS: Well, we could just use four and have two
people hold on to the same cannonball.

03:10:25.518 --> 03:10:30.649
LIAM: Yeah, that makes sense. Nott and I are
sharing one.

03:10:30.649 --> 03:10:35.761
MATT: Okay. You maneuver the boat slowly also
closer to where Frumpkin saw because when Frumpkin

03:10:35.761 --> 03:10:39.699
found it, it was at an angle away from you, which
is how it was just beyond the range of a thousand

03:10:39.699 --> 03:10:45.301
feet. Moving over, it's probably close to 700 feet
below.

03:10:45.301 --> 03:10:49.294
LIAM: So Frumpkin is pinwheeling in front of all
of us leading the way.

03:10:49.294 --> 03:10:50.499
MATT: Okay.

03:10:50.499 --> 03:10:53.048
TRAVIS: I don't suppose we have 700 feet of rope
on this ship, do we?

03:10:53.048 --> 03:10:56.419
LAURA: Probably not.

03:10:56.419 --> 03:11:00.577
SAM: We have an anchor. It can only go down so
far, but I don't know how--

03:11:00.577 --> 03:11:02.228
MARISHA: That's true. How far does the anchor go?

03:11:02.228 --> 03:11:04.067
SAM: 200 feet? 100 feet?

03:11:04.067 --> 03:11:05.415
MATT: It's not going to go that far.

03:11:05.415 --> 03:11:09.452
LIAM: No, ships don't go to anchor in the middle
of the ocean. They just float.

03:11:09.452 --> 03:11:14.805
TRAVIS: If you're ready, take a seat on the rail
and I'll hop up and put my butt out towards the sea.

03:11:14.805 --> 03:11:16.363
LAURA: It's going to be dark down there.

03:11:16.363 --> 03:11:17.832
MARISHA: Do we have light spells?

03:11:17.832 --> 03:11:19.517
LAURA: I don't.

03:11:19.517 --> 03:11:20.749
TRAVIS: Yasha does.

03:11:20.749 --> 03:11:21.823
TALIESIN: I do.

03:11:21.823 --> 03:11:23.355
LIAM: (popping)

03:11:23.355 --> 03:11:25.106
MATT: Dancing Lights. You cast Light on?

03:11:25.106 --> 03:11:26.184
TALIESIN: On my staff.

03:11:26.184 --> 03:11:28.425
MATT: Yasha casts Light on her sword, the
Magician's Judge.

03:11:28.425 --> 03:11:29.723
SAM: I need a minute!

03:11:29.723 --> 03:11:30.771
TRAVIS: You need a minute?

03:11:30.771 --> 03:11:32.684
SAM: I'm going to drink heavily.

03:11:32.684 --> 03:11:34.795
MATT: To the point where you're intoxicated?

03:11:34.795 --> 03:11:36.379
SAM: To the point of intoxication.

03:11:36.379 --> 03:11:37.272
MATT: Okay.

03:11:37.272 --> 03:11:45.506
LIAM: That's important because I switched the
Transmuter's Stone away from darkvision, so I

03:11:45.506 --> 03:11:50.173
cannot see in low light, so it's got to be guiding
lights for me.

03:11:50.173 --> 03:11:54.637
LAURA: I'm going to take Sprinkle out of my
hood--

03:11:54.637 --> 03:11:56.000
TRAVIS: Ah, smart.

03:11:56.000 --> 03:11:58.569
MARISHA: Oh, buddy.

03:11:58.569 --> 03:12:04.606
MATT: This poor little-- it's better over the days
that it's been able to spend with you since

03:12:04.606 --> 03:12:08.894
Darktow, but this ferret's been through quite a
few experiences.

03:12:08.894 --> 03:12:16.416
LAURA: You're like a super ferret. You're like the
strongest little animal I've ever seen. I mean, really.

03:12:16.416 --> 03:12:19.433
MATT: (ferret chattering) Then he curls up. He
hears a loud noise (startled chittering).

03:12:19.433 --> 03:12:20.654
TALIESIN: Scarred for life.

03:12:20.654 --> 03:12:22.189
TRAVIS: He's just fucked.

03:12:22.189 --> 03:12:23.478
LAURA: Orly?

03:12:23.478 --> 03:12:24.842
MARISHA: He's a rescue.

03:12:24.842 --> 03:12:29.659
MATT: "Hmm?" I can't remember which eye it is
anymore. I'll have to go check. "Mmm?"

03:12:29.659 --> 03:12:35.201
LAURA: Do you like weasels?

03:12:35.201 --> 03:12:38.046
SAM: That's a weird opener.

03:12:38.046 --> 03:12:40.815
TALIESIN: It never ends well. There's no right
answer to that question.

03:12:40.815 --> 03:12:42.030
MATT: "Why?"

03:12:42.030 --> 03:12:45.770
LAURA: I have a weasel and I don't want to take
him underwater.

03:12:45.770 --> 03:12:47.722
TALIESIN: Water weasel.

03:12:47.722 --> 03:12:52.633
MATT: You watch as Orly's head retracts into the
shell slightly with this look of--

03:12:52.633 --> 03:12:54.336
LAURA: Orly.

03:12:54.336 --> 03:13:00.389
MATT: Marius steps up and goes like, "I'm happy to
look after him. Actually been quite a while since

03:13:00.389 --> 03:13:02.293
"I've seen a pet."

03:13:02.293 --> 03:13:03.639
MARISHA: Wait. Who said that?

03:13:03.639 --> 03:13:05.290
SAM and MATT: Marius LePual.

03:13:05.290 --> 03:13:08.578
MATT: Who you've dragged all the way from
Nicodranas--

03:13:08.578 --> 03:13:12.437
TRAVIS: But he's got a good tan now and some
scars, his clothes are kind of fucked up.

03:13:12.437 --> 03:13:15.212
LAURA: He's like Guy Threepwood now.

03:13:15.212 --> 03:13:19.558
MATT: He does look a little more ocean-wearied. As
prim and proper and put together as Marius was at

03:13:19.558 --> 03:13:23.561
Nicodranas, he's definitely rocking more of a
Pirates of Penzance thing now.

03:13:23.561 --> 03:13:27.682
LIAM: He went from level two to three. Doing
good.

03:13:27.682 --> 03:13:29.932
LAURA: You'll take good care of him?

03:13:29.932 --> 03:13:31.061
MATT: "Of course!"

03:13:31.061 --> 03:13:37.556
LAURA: If you don't, I will know and I will give
you a tattoo. If you do take good care of him,

03:13:37.556 --> 03:13:41.957
though, I will give you a better tattoo.

03:13:41.957 --> 03:13:44.651
MATT: "Are those the only options?"

03:13:44.651 --> 03:13:46.664
LAURA: I mean, if you want.

03:13:46.664 --> 03:13:49.921
MATT: "Okay. Hello-- oh!" (nervous laughter)

03:13:49.921 --> 03:13:56.309
LAURA: He likes to eat fruit. He likes to eat
cheese. He likes to eat bugs.

03:13:56.309 --> 03:13:57.600
MATT: "Right."

03:13:57.600 --> 03:14:00.718
SAM: I think we only have the one food that you've
been creating on the ship.

03:14:00.718 --> 03:14:02.432
LAURA: He likes it if you talk to him.

03:14:02.432 --> 03:14:03.414
TALIESIN: We have bugs and cheese.

03:14:03.414 --> 03:14:04.332
LAURA: Yeah, we got bugs and cheese.

03:14:04.332 --> 03:14:10.438
MATT: "Okay. Well, come. Let's get you some cheese
and-- oh, that's my hand you're peeing in, okay."

03:14:10.438 --> 03:14:12.060
TALIESIN: We always got bugs and cheese, man.

03:14:12.060 --> 03:14:15.470
MATT: He carries him off. All right, you gather
your supplies, you gather your cannonballs.

03:14:15.470 --> 03:14:17.602
MARISHA: Oh my god.

03:14:17.602 --> 03:14:21.850
TRAVIS: On the count of three, when you're ready,
you'll lean backwards off the rail and fall into

03:14:21.850 --> 03:14:22.951
the water.

03:14:22.951 --> 03:14:24.802
LAURA: On the count of three, when you're ready.

03:14:24.802 --> 03:14:34.794
MATT: As it stands, the cannonballs are smooth,
solid metal. How are you bringing them down with you?

03:14:34.794 --> 03:14:36.050
TALIESIN: There's a couple of options here.

03:14:36.050 --> 03:14:37.412
LAURA: We're going to hold on to the sides.

03:14:37.412 --> 03:14:41.386
TALIESIN: Well, we want to be able to carry them
so if we have some small bags maybe?

03:14:41.386 --> 03:14:43.710
MARISHA: Like rope or chain? Oh! Yeah.

03:14:43.710 --> 03:14:45.517
TALIESIN: We can just put them in a bag that we
can hold.

03:14:45.517 --> 03:14:48.520
MATT: That can be done. You do have a few sacks.

03:14:48.520 --> 03:14:55.440
LIAM: They're iron, right? I would say that with
Nott piggybacking, Caleb would take his dagger and

03:14:55.440 --> 03:15:00.020
transmute it into iron to meld with the cannonball
and grip it that way.

03:15:00.020 --> 03:15:01.960
TRAVIS: Ooh, make a little handle.

03:15:01.960 --> 03:15:03.661
MATT: I'll allow it, yeah.

03:15:03.661 --> 03:15:05.312
LIAM: Thanks.

03:15:05.936 --> 03:15:09.491
MATT: As you place the dagger against it, there's
a brief moment where the dagger seems to shift

03:15:09.491 --> 03:15:13.694
energy and you slip it inside of it and at that
point, the handle is now solid with the

03:15:13.694 --> 03:15:18.262
cannonball, so one cannonball has a handle.
Another one, a sack around it. Actually, a few of

03:15:18.262 --> 03:15:20.107
them you can put sacks around it, so--

03:15:20.107 --> 03:15:22.061
TRAVIS: You want to share a cannonball, Jester?

03:15:22.061 --> 03:15:22.960
LAURA: Sure, Fjord.

03:15:22.960 --> 03:15:23.659
TRAVIS: Okay.

03:15:23.659 --> 03:15:29.981
MARISHA: Cad, you and me? What's Yasha doing, is
she coming with us or is she invigorated by the storm?

03:15:29.981 --> 03:15:31.578
TRAVIS: She gets her own cannonball because
she's--

03:15:31.578 --> 03:15:32.644
MATT: Yeah, she's coming with you.

03:15:32.644 --> 03:15:37.697
TRAVIS: Yeah, she's just like that. Just holding
it like a beast.

03:15:37.697 --> 03:15:38.879
LIAM: Palming it.

03:15:38.879 --> 03:15:41.362
MARISHA: Yeah. Globetrotters.

03:15:41.362 --> 03:15:45.462
TRAVIS: Ready? One, two, three.

03:15:45.462 --> 03:15:46.409
LAURA: Oh god!

03:15:46.409 --> 03:15:47.640
SAM: (screaming)

03:15:47.640 --> 03:15:59.821
MATT: You splash and break the surface of the
ocean. As you all begin to sink slowly beneath the

03:15:59.821 --> 03:16:05.586
waves, the light begins to get darker and darker
the further down you pass. The shades of

03:16:05.586 --> 03:16:13.966
green-blue begin to turn to a deep green-brown,
and even that light begins to fade, just having

03:16:13.966 --> 03:16:19.620
the few points of light that you are bringing
along with yourselves towards the bottom of the ocean.

03:16:19.620 --> 03:16:22.812
TRAVIS: I try to catch Nott. How is she doing?

03:16:22.812 --> 03:16:24.681
SAM: Eyes totally closed.

03:16:24.681 --> 03:16:26.703
TRAVIS: Are you breathing well? I give her a--

03:16:26.703 --> 03:16:28.542
MATT: Nott has not taken a breath yet, actually.

03:16:28.542 --> 03:16:30.491
TRAVIS: International sign for breathe.

03:16:30.491 --> 03:16:36.660
MATT: You get to a point, Nott, where your lungs
hurt so much you cannot help but breathe in, and

03:16:36.660 --> 03:16:40.379
there is a moment of panic as suddenly water
rushes into your lungs and the nightmare you've

03:16:40.379 --> 03:16:42.576
had many times kicks in.

03:16:42.576 --> 03:16:47.346
TRAVIS: Actually, that means go down.

03:16:47.346 --> 03:16:50.541
SAM: Shit.

03:16:57.136 --> 03:17:00.658
MATT: It takes a little bit to adjust and anxiety
is still spiked in you, but you begin to find

03:17:00.658 --> 03:17:06.004
yourself breathing water in and out-- like thicker
air, but still air-- and it's more comfortable

03:17:06.004 --> 03:17:08.176
than you expected.

03:17:08.176 --> 03:17:09.854
LAURA: Can we talk down here?

03:17:09.854 --> 03:17:10.900
MATT: You can.

03:17:10.900 --> 03:17:11.810
LAURA: We can?

03:17:11.810 --> 03:17:17.045
MATT: It doesn't have the same volume you do above
water, which means you can cast spells underwater

03:17:17.045 --> 03:17:17.898
without issue.

03:17:17.898 --> 03:17:18.474
LIAM: We can?

03:17:18.474 --> 03:17:26.430
MATT: Yes, same as you had before. It carries
vibration and sound travels far, but it loses

03:17:26.430 --> 03:17:32.582
enunciation at longer distances, but you can hear
voices longer.

03:17:32.582 --> 03:17:36.974
LIAM: There are four globules of light slowly
circling around.

03:17:36.974 --> 03:17:43.763
SAM: (gurgling) When we get back to the surface, I
will kill you.

03:17:43.763 --> 03:17:45.356
MARISHA: That was pretty good, though.

03:17:45.356 --> 03:17:47.858
MATT: Oh, this is going to be awful.

03:17:47.858 --> 03:17:52.677
TRAVIS: (gurgling) Well listen, Nott, as long as
we're down here--

03:17:52.677 --> 03:17:56.765
LIAM: Cannot do that joke anymore. That joke has
past.

03:17:58.902 --> 03:18:07.566
MATT: Your feet find the bottom of the ocean after
minutes. Ten minutes. Who knows how much time has

03:18:07.566 --> 03:18:11.583
past? It seemed longer than you expected until you
eventually you hit the bottom of the ocean.

03:18:11.583 --> 03:18:13.330
MARISHA: Look up. What do I see?

03:18:13.330 --> 03:18:19.118
MATT: You see the faint bit of light above where
it marks where the sunlight is hitting the waves,

03:18:19.118 --> 03:18:28.009
but it's an impossible distance from you from this
perspective. There are heavy, slowly shifting

03:18:28.009 --> 03:18:39.351
arms, waving tassels of kelp and sea vegetation
slightly drifting and moving with every faint bit

03:18:39.351 --> 03:18:45.801
of water that gets maneuvered through with each
wave and push as it goes, and you can feel it move

03:18:45.801 --> 03:18:51.295
you a few inches and you have to readjust as each
one pushes through.

03:18:53.165 --> 03:18:55.896
LAURA: It's like another world.

03:18:57.121 --> 03:19:01.008
MATT: You realize there shouldn't be waves this
deep necessarily.

03:19:01.008 --> 03:19:02.624
MARISHA: Where are they coming from?

03:19:02.624 --> 03:19:10.310
MATT: You glance over and watch as a large
creature is not that far away from you.

03:19:10.310 --> 03:19:12.577
LAURA: I cast Pass Without a Trace on all of us.

03:19:12.577 --> 03:19:14.863
TALIESIN: I dim the light.

03:19:14.863 --> 03:19:18.066
LIAM: Can't see anymore.

03:19:18.066 --> 03:19:27.281
MATT: You hear a faint (whale singing) and glance
over the left. You can see a whale making its way

03:19:27.281 --> 03:19:31.101
through the water about 50, 60 feet from you.

03:19:31.101 --> 03:19:32.397
LIAM: I can't see shit.

03:19:32.397 --> 03:19:33.961
MATT: Not with a--

03:19:33.961 --> 03:19:36.008
MARISHA: I put my goggles on by the way--

03:19:36.008 --> 03:19:37.893
LIAM: You're good. I'm blind and are you blind?

03:19:37.893 --> 03:19:45.520
MATT: He still has the light. You can still see;
Caduceus and Yasha still have the light on their weapons.

03:19:45.520 --> 03:19:52.082
TALIESIN: My weapon glows but I did snuff it down.
I was waiting until we knew that we were okay. I

03:19:52.082 --> 03:19:54.035
move my light over to him.

03:19:54.035 --> 03:19:57.667
MATT: The whale continues on, slowly moving, not
really acknowledging your presence. You can see

03:19:57.667 --> 03:20:00.117
two other smaller whales alongside it.

03:20:00.117 --> 03:20:02.020
TRAVIS: Aww, baby calves.

03:20:02.020 --> 03:20:09.591
TALIESIN: Hey. Technically they can understand
me.

03:20:09.591 --> 03:20:16.769
MATT: Everyone make an investigation check. This
will be perception. Underwater, perception.

03:20:16.769 --> 03:20:18.288
SAM: Disadvantage!

03:20:18.288 --> 03:20:19.764
MATT: Yep.

03:20:19.764 --> 03:20:21.277
MARISHA: Natural one.

03:20:21.277 --> 03:20:22.987
TRAVIS: 19.

03:20:22.987 --> 03:20:24.065
LIAM: Nine.

03:20:24.065 --> 03:20:25.716
SAM: Four.

03:20:25.716 --> 03:20:26.822
LAURA: 14.

03:20:26.822 --> 03:20:27.949
TALIESIN: At disadvantage?

03:20:27.949 --> 03:20:28.808
SAM: No. Just me.

03:20:28.808 --> 03:20:29.912
TALIESIN: Oh, 16.

03:20:29.912 --> 03:20:31.589
MATT: Roll for Yasha as well.

03:20:32.726 --> 03:20:35.558
TRAVIS: Five for her.

03:20:35.558 --> 03:20:43.276
MATT: Oof. All right, overall party: not so great.
It takes you a little while, about two to three

03:20:43.276 --> 03:20:48.678
hours of searching the bottom of the ocean. You're
starting to get a little hungry again from all the

03:20:48.678 --> 03:20:55.232
strenuous activity of moving and dragging these
cannonballs with you to keep you weighted down so

03:20:55.232 --> 03:21:00.601
you can step across the surface. You come past
some deep sea corals and beautiful colorful

03:21:00.601 --> 03:21:06.305
visions and schools of fish scooting and coasting
around. At one point, they swarm past you, and you

03:21:06.305 --> 03:21:13.592
feel them tickling past your torso before they
skitter past. Eventually, this lift begins to

03:21:13.592 --> 03:21:22.080
descend into a small bowl or at least a point
where the shelf begins to head in a downward

03:21:22.080 --> 03:21:30.062
direction at a decline. Within the next 15 or so
minutes of traveling in that direction, you see

03:21:30.062 --> 03:21:36.430
the outline of a familiar ship.

03:21:36.430 --> 03:21:41.102
TRAVIS: I push forward towards it. Point and start
to swim.

03:21:41.102 --> 03:21:47.428
MATT: All right. As you all gather in behind Fjord
making your way in the direction of this long

03:21:47.428 --> 03:21:49.976
forgotten shipwreck, we'll pick it up there next
week.

03:21:49.976 --> 03:21:52.709
(groaning)

03:21:54.382 --> 03:21:56.434
MATT: You'll find out next week!

03:21:56.434 --> 03:21:57.546
SAM: Oh my god, Matt.

03:21:57.546 --> 03:21:59.668
MARISHA and TRAVIS: What a game!

03:21:59.668 --> 03:22:01.042
MATT: That was a good session, guys.

03:22:01.042 --> 03:22:08.008
LIAM: One of the best ever. So many great games!

03:22:08.008 --> 03:22:15.055
MATT: That went some interesting places. There's a
number of scenarios that didn't happen.

03:22:15.055 --> 03:22:18.702
TRAVIS: There was a number of scenarios that
didn't happen?

03:22:18.702 --> 03:22:21.923
SAM: I feel like there was so much more on the
island that we did not--

03:22:21.923 --> 03:22:23.402
MATT: There's a lot more on that island.

03:22:23.402 --> 03:22:28.303
SAM: There's Allison, there was shit alleys, and
there was all kinds of fun stuff.

03:22:28.303 --> 03:22:31.932
TALIESIN: Just because we're banished doesn't mean
we're never going back.

03:22:31.932 --> 03:22:34.487
MARISHA: We keep pissing off the towns.

03:22:34.487 --> 03:22:39.192
TALIESIN: Oh, I'm so sorry. Like a cop said
"you're trespassing" and now we're just going to

03:22:39.192 --> 03:22:40.757
never trespass again?

03:22:40.757 --> 03:22:41.640
TRAVIS: Well said.

03:22:41.640 --> 03:22:44.891
MATT: Yes, we're not because we're law abiding
citizens.

03:22:44.891 --> 03:22:49.142
MARISHA: I was going to say, when you go into a
convenience store and it's got the "Have you seen

03:22:49.142 --> 03:22:50.706
"this person?"

03:22:50.706 --> 03:22:52.935
LIAM: This campaign is a social experiment.

03:22:52.935 --> 03:22:59.280
MATT: Oh yeah. This has gone really interesting,
fun places. Well, thank you guys. I'm excited to

03:22:59.280 --> 03:23:08.567
pick this up next week at the shipwreck. Thank you
guys for tuning in. Yeah, I missed this-- two

03:23:08.567 --> 03:23:10.889
weeks off and suddenly--

03:23:10.889 --> 03:23:12.330
LIAM: All the dead.

03:23:12.330 --> 03:23:14.267
TALIESIN: We were freaking out all for two weeks
straight.

03:23:14.267 --> 03:23:15.208
LAURA: Yeah.

03:23:15.208 --> 03:23:17.314
MATT: You guys had some good, solid plans.

03:23:17.314 --> 03:23:19.869
MARISHA: Our plan was okay.

03:23:19.869 --> 03:23:20.790
MATT: Yeah.

03:23:20.790 --> 03:23:25.311
TALIESIN: That was entirely worth the amount of
data it took up on my phone.

03:23:25.311 --> 03:23:26.974
LIAM: It worked.

03:23:26.974 --> 03:23:30.504
TRAVIS: I think all anyone asked is for some
slight improvements in our planning over the

03:23:30.504 --> 03:23:32.229
years. Slight improvements.

03:23:32.229 --> 03:23:33.861
LIAM: Yeah, it worked.

03:23:33.861 --> 03:23:38.953
MATT: Man, most of D&amp;amp;D is about plans that go
fucking tits up the minute you try and talk about

03:23:38.953 --> 03:23:45.771
it. Everyone is like, "Oh, they planned so
terribly." Every D&amp;amp;D game, everyone plans

03:23:45.771 --> 03:23:50.679
terribly. Sometimes plans go great, and those are
the ones you remember when you compare it to other

03:23:50.679 --> 03:23:55.317
people. "Oh, we're great planners. Remember that
two times over the past 18 years we played where

03:23:55.317 --> 03:24:00.269
"our plans went great? Those are the times we'll
always bring up and judging other people's plans."

03:24:00.269 --> 03:24:04.128
Yeah, everyone has some good plans every now and
then. More often than not, plans go pretty shitty

03:24:04.128 --> 03:24:11.178
and that's fun. Anyway, thank you all for coming
and watching along with us after the two week

03:24:11.178 --> 03:24:18.737
break. Thank you D&amp;amp;D Beyond for being our amazing
friends and sponsors. We'll see you in a week and

03:24:18.737 --> 03:24:21.226
remember we love you all--

03:24:21.226 --> 03:24:26.909
LIAM: (creepy voice) Is it Thursday yet?
(growling)

03:24:26.909 --> 03:24:28.682
MARISHA: You did this.

03:24:28.682 --> 03:24:30.524
SAM: Yeah, I did.

03:24:30.524 --> 03:24:31.629
MARISHA: This is you.

03:24:31.629 --> 03:24:32.970
SAM: Sorry.

03:24:32.970 --> 03:24:36.169
LIAM: I'm so upset. (normal voice) Take it away,
Matt.

03:24:36.169 --> 03:24:39.208
MATT: Is it Thursday yet? Good night, everybody.

03:24:39.208 --> 03:24:42.464
(laughter)

03:24:42.464 --> 03:24:49.996
[music]

